:has_definition ""A layer of estuarine water which extends from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth and from the shore to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters."" .

,The estuarine coastal upper water column is a multifaceted type of layer within aquatic estuarine environments. It serves as an interface between liquid air and water, and it also represents the surface of an astronomical body. This layer is part of, or at least includes, some portion of the estuarine coastal surface layer. In its positioning, it is adjacent to shorelines as well as to the estuarine coastal pycnocline. The definition of the estuarine coastal upper water column encapsulates its nature succinctly: it is a layer of estuarine water which extends from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth, and from the shore to a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.",7,True
:has_definition ""A pycnocline which is part of an estuarine water body, spanning from the shore to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters."" .

,The estuarine coastal pycnocline is a type of pycnocline, aquatic estuarine layer, and is at least adjacent to some shoreline, estuarine coastal upper water column, and estuarine coastal lower water column. It is defined as a pycnocline which is part of an estuarine water body, spanning from the shore to a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.",6,True

:has_definition ""A layer of estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuarine bed and from the shore to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters."" .

,The estuarine coastal lower water column is classified as a type of aquatic estuarine layer, which is inherently adjacent to both some shoreline and an estuarine coastal pycnocline. It is defined as a layer of estuarine water extending from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuarine bed, and from the shore to a fiat boundary, where below the water column, the estuary bed reaches a depth of 4 meters.",4,True

:has_definition ""A layer of estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

,The estuarine open water surface layer is classified as a type of aquatic estuarine layer, a liquid air water interface layer, and a surface of an astronomical body. It is defined as a layer of estuarine water extending a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed. This layer stretches from a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to the most distal end of the estuary from the coast.",4,True

:has_definition ""A layer of estuarine water which extends from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

,The estuarine open water upper water column is a type of aquatic estuarine layer, a liquid air water interface layer, and the surface of an astronomical body. The estuarine open water upper water column is defined as a layer of estuarine water extending from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth, and from a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast.",6,True

:has_definition ""A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from the land-water interface to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters."" .

,The estuarine tidal riverine coastal surface layer is a type of estuarine coastal surface layer that is primarily composed of fresh water. It is defined as a layer of fresh estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from the land-water interface to a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters.,3,True

:has_definition ""A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth and from the land-water interface to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters."" .

,The estuarine tidal riverine coastal upper water column is categorized under the estuarine coastal upper water column. :has_definition ""A body of water which is primarily composed of saline water.""

It is a type of water body that intersects with the category of entities that are at least composed primarily of saline water. Moreover, a saline water body is also referred to as a saline body of water.",5,True
:has_definition ""A body of water which is primarily composed of freshwater, with low solute content.""

,A fresh water body is defined as a body of water that is primarily composed of freshwater and has a low solute content. Additionally, a fresh water body is equivalent to the intersection of a water body and an entity that is at least composed primarily of some fresh water. :has_definition ""A body of water which is primarily composed of brackish water.""

This indicates that a brackish water body is a type of saline water body as well as a type of entity that is at least composed primarily of brackish water. :has_definition ""A layer of estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

,The estuarine open water lower water column is a type of aquatic estuarine layer and is also a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some estuarine open water pycnocline. It is defined as a layer of estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuary bed, and from a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to the end of the estuary most distal from the coast.",3,True

:has_definition ""A pycnocline which is part of an estuarine water body, spanning from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

:has_definition ""An estuarine coastal pycnocline which is composed primarily of fresh tidal water."" .

,The estuarine tidal riverine coastal pycnocline is a specific type of estuarine coastal pycnocline that is primarily composed of fresh tidal water. Its definition elaborates it as an estuarine coastal pycnocline characterized by being predominantly made up of fresh tidal water.,3,True

:has_definition ""A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuarine bed and from the land-water interface to a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters."" .

:has_definition ""A layer of fresh, tidal estuarine water which extends a few centimeters from the surface of the water column towards the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

,The estuarine tidal riverine open water surface layer is a specific kind of estuarine open water surface layer. This layer is characterized primarily by its composition, which is predominantly fresh water. It is defined as a layer of fresh, tidal estuarine water that starts just a few centimeters from the water column's surface and extends towards the estuary bed. This layer extends from a flat boundary, where the estuary bed beneath the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters, to the end of the estuary that is most distal from the coast.",3,True

:has_definition ""A layer of fresh, tidal estuarine water which extends from the surface of the water column to the pycnocline or mid-depth and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters until the end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

The estuarine tidal riverine open water upper water column is characterized by being a layer of fresh, tidal estuarine water that stretches from the water surface down to the pycnocline or mid-depth. This extends from a defined boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters up to the furthest end of the estuary from the coast.",4,True
:has_definition ""An estuarine open water pycnocline which is composed primarily of fresh tidal water."" .

,The estuarine tidal riverine open water pycnocline is a specific type of estuarine open water pycnocline that is primarily composed of fresh water. It is defined as an estuarine open water pycnocline composed primarily of fresh tidal water.,3,True

:has_definition ""A layer of fresh estuarine water which extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuary bed and from a fiat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to end of the estuary most distal from the coast."" .

,The estuarine tidal riverine open water lower water column is both a type of aquatic estuarine layer and something that is at least adjacent to some estuarine open water pycnocline. It is defined as a layer of fresh estuarine water that extends from an estuarine pycnocline or mid-depth to the estuary bed, and from a flat boundary where the estuary bed below the water column reaches a depth of 4 meters to the end of the estuary most distal from the coast.",3,True
:has_definition ""A biogeochemical cycle which has nitrogen-bearing chemical entities as participants.""

,Nitrogen cycling, also known as the nitrogen cycle, is a type of biogeochemical cycling. It is characterized by its involvement with nitrogen atoms, both as a process that includes these atoms as inputs and as a system engaging chemical entities that contain nitrogen atoms as parts. Furthermore, nitrogen cycling is defined as a biogeochemical cycle where nitrogen-bearing chemical entities participate. This process intersects with broader biogeochemical cycling and systems that incorporate nitrogen atoms in any form.",6,True
:has_definition ""A biogeochemical cycle which has sulfur-bearing chemical entities as participants.""

,Sulfur cycling is synonymous with a process that intersects biogeochemical cycling and processes that at least have some sulfur atoms as input. It is a specific type of biogeochemical cycling, as well as a type of process that involves participants which are an intersection of chemical entities and entities that have at least some part made of sulfur atoms. Additionally, sulfur cycling is characterized by processes that include sulfur atoms as input. It is defined as a biogeochemical cycle which involves sulfur-bearing chemical entities as participants. Furthermore, sulfur cycling has an exact synonym ""sulphur cycling"" and a related synonym ""sulfur cycle.""",7,True
:has_definition ""A biogeochemical cycle which has phosphorous-bearing chemical entities as participants.""

,Phosphorous cycling is defined as a biogeochemical cycle that involves phosphorus-bearing chemical entities as participants, which makes it a specific type of biogeochemical cycling. It is characterized by processes that at least have an input of some phosphorus atom and includes participation from entities that are at the intersection of chemical entities and those that have phosphorus atoms as part of their composition. Additionally, phosphorous cycling is commonly referred to by its related synonym, the phosphorous cycle.",6,True

:has_definition ""A tidal flow process which occurs in an ocean or sea and during which tidal movements generate advective flows, often amplified in velocity when moving through an inlet, pass or channel.""

,Marine tidal flow process is a type of tidal flow process and is also a kind of phenomenon that occurs in environments such as the ocean, sea, and estuaries. It is defined as a tidal flow process which happens in an ocean or sea, wherein tidal movements produce advective flows. These flows are often amplified in velocity when they move through an inlet, pass, or channel. Additionally, the marine tidal flow process is synonymously related to tidal flow.",4,True

:has_definition ""A material transport process during which a volume of material is displaced due to a disequilibrium in physical forces and during which 1) the qualities that inhere in that volume and 2) the processes that are unfolding within it are largely unchanged.""@en

,The advective transport process is synonymous with advective transport and is defined as a material transport process during which a volume of material is displaced due to a disequilibrium in physical forces. During this displacement, the qualities that inhere in that volume and the processes that unfold within it are largely unchanged. It is identical to a phenomenon that lies at the intersection of a material transport process and something that possesses at least one advective characteristic. Furthermore, the advective transport process is categorized as a type of material transport process and also as a type that partially encompasses convective transport processes and material diffusion processes. Additionally, it is recognized as a type that exhibits at least one advective characteristic.",7,True
:has_definition ""An ice mass which is attached to a bed underneath a body of water.""

,Anchor ice is a type of ice mass, which is also known as Caro 0000003, and is characterized by being at least partially surrounded by some liquid water and attached to some submerged bed. It is defined as an ice mass which is attached to a bed underneath a body of water. Additionally, anchor ice is exactly synonymous with bottom-fast ice.",6,True
:has_definition ""A marine current which is maintained by a tidal flow process.""

,Marine tidal flow is a type of marine current, which is maintained by a tidal flow process, and it is also a type of something that at least contains a process some marine tidal flow process. Additionally, marine tidal flow has a related synonym, marine tidal current.",4,True
:has_definition ""Anchor ice which is attached to a riverbed.""

,Riverine anchor ice is a type of anchor ice that is partially surrounded by river water and is adjacent to a river bed. It is defined as anchor ice which is attached to a riverbed. Additionally, riverine anchor ice is exactly synonymous with riverine bottom-fast ice.",5,True

:has_definition ""A marine zone in which ocean waters undergo a diurnal (once per day) tidal oscillation - with one high and one low tide per day - due to the supression of a second daily oscillation by the geometry of the ocean basin and obstructions presented by land masses.""

,The diurnal marine tidal flow zone is a type of marine tidal flow zone and falls under a category that necessarily involves the process of diurnal marine tidal flow. It is defined as a marine zone where ocean waters experience a diurnal (once per day) tidal oscillation, characterized by one high and one low tide each day. This occurs due to the suppression of a second daily oscillation by the geometry of the ocean basin and obstructions presented by land masses. Additionally, the diurnal marine tidal flow zone is synonymously related to diurnal tidal flow.",4,True
:has_definition ""A tidal flow process which occurs once per day in ocean waters where a second daily oscillation is blocked by land masses or ocean basin geometry."" .

,Diurnal marine tidal flow process, alternatively known as diurnal tidal flow, is a type of marine tidal flow process that occurs at least in some diurnal marine tidal flow zones and has the quality of being somewhat discontinuous. It is defined as a tidal flow process that occurs once per day in ocean waters where a second daily oscillation is blocked by land masses or ocean basin geometry.",5,True
:has_definition ""A marine tidal flow zone in which ocean waters undergo a semi-diurnal (twice per day) tidal oscillation - with two high and two low tides per day of roughly equal amplitude.""

,The semi-diurnal marine tidal flow zone is a type of marine tidal flow zone that encompasses a process known as the semi-diurnal marine tidal flow process. This zone is defined as a marine tidal flow zone in which ocean waters undergo a semi-diurnal (twice per day) tidal oscillation, characterized by two high and two low tides each day of roughly equal amplitude. Additionally, the semi-diurnal marine tidal flow zone is synonymously related to semi-diurnal tidal flow.",4,True

:has_definition ""An environmental zone in which varying gravitational forces from astronomical bodies, combined with the rotation of the astronomical body containing the zone, cause marine waters to undergo periodic depth oscillations (tides)."" .

,The marine tidal flow zone is a type of marine environmental zone, which is part of, or at least partially overlaps, some ocean and some sea coast. This zone is characterized by containing processes such as marine tidal flow. It is defined as an environmental zone where varying gravitational forces from astronomical bodies, combined with the rotation of the astronomical body containing the zone, cause marine waters to undergo periodic depth oscillations, known as tides.",5,True

:has_definition ""A water flow process during which movements of water masses caused by varying gravitational and rotational forces from astronomical bodies, combined with the rotation of the astronomical body containing the water mass, cause waters to undergo periodic depth oscillations (tides)."" .

,The tidal flow process is categorized as a type of mass liquid flow and also a type of water flow process. Additionally, it is defined as a type of process that, at the very least, is part of something involving advective transport processes and includes participation from liquid water. The tidal flow process is described as a water flow process where movements of water masses, influenced by varying gravitational and rotational forces from astronomical bodies, along with the rotation of the astronomical body containing the water mass, lead to periodic depth oscillations known as tides. An alternative term for the tidal flow process is ""tidal flow.""",5,True
:has_definition ""A marine tidal flow process which occurs twice per day, resulting in two high and two low tides per day, both of roughly equal amplitude."" .

,The semi-diurnal marine tidal flow process, which can also be referred to as semi-diurnal tidal flow, is a specific type of marine tidal flow process. It is characterized by occurring at least within some semi-diurnal marine tidal flow zones and possesses the quality of being somewhat discontinuous. This process is defined as a marine tidal flow that happens twice per day, resulting in two high and two low tides each day, both of approximately equal amplitude.",5,True
:has_definition ""Anchor ice which is attached to a riverbed where a river flows into a marine water body and which is formed by the freezing of freshwater seeping out of the riverbed's sediments.""

,Freshwater seep riverine anchor ice is a type of riverine anchor ice, which is also adjacent to some river mouth. It is defined as anchor ice attached to a riverbed where a river flows into a marine water body, formed by the freezing of freshwater seeping out of the riverbed's sediments. Moreover, it has exact synonyms including fresh water seep riverine anchor ice, fresh water seep riverine bottom-fast ice, and freshwater seep riverine bottom-fast ice.",6,True
:has_definition ""An ice mass which is suspended in a water body, being sufficiently buoyant for part of the mass to breach the surface of that water body."" .

,A floating ice mass is defined as an ice mass that is suspended in a water body, being sufficiently buoyant for part of the mass to breach the surface of that water body. It is the same as the intersection of something that is an ice mass and something that is at least partially surrounded by a water body, as well as something that is at least partially surrounded by an atmosphere, and something that at least has the quality of some buoyancy. Furthermore, a floating ice mass is classified as a type of ice mass, a type of something that is at least partially surrounded by a water body, a type of something that is at least partially surrounded by an atmosphere, and a type of something that at least has the quality of buoyancy.",6,True

:has_definition ""An action of exogenic processes (such as water flow or wind) which remove environmental material from one location on the surface of an astronomical body, transporting it to another location where it is deposited."" .

,Erosion is identified as a material transport process that involves at least some environmental material and some planetary crust as participants. It is defined as an action of exogenic processes, such as water flow or wind, which remove environmental material from one location on the surface of an astronomical body and transport it to another location where it is deposited.",4,True
:has_definition ""A zone on a glacier which is roughly linear and where the rates of ice ablation and accumulation are approximately equal.""

,The glacial equilibrium line is a type of environmental zone characterized by processual equilibrium. It encompasses processes of both glacial ice ablation and glacial ice gain, indicating its role in the balance of ice dynamics. Moreover, it possesses a linear quality and is situated adjacent to both the glacial ice accumulation zone and the glacial ice ablation zone. The glacial equilibrium line is defined as a zone on a glacier that is roughly linear, where the rates of ice ablation and accumulation are approximately equal. It is also known by several related synonyms, including equilibrium limit, equilibrium line, firn limit, and firn line.",11,True
:has_definition ""A zone in which the deposition and accumulation of an environmental material occurs.""

,A material accumulation zone is a type of environmental zone that at least contains some material accumulation process. It is defined as a zone in which the deposition and accumulation of an environmental material occurs. Additionally, the material accumulation zone is also related to the synonym ""accumulation zone.""",4,True
:has_definition ""A zone in which processes resulting in the removal of one or more environmental materials have higher rates than pocesses which result in their deposition and accumulation.""

,A material decumulation zone is a type of environmental zone and also a type of zone that at least contains processes involving material decumulation. It is defined as a zone in which processes resulting in the removal of one or more environmental materials have higher rates than processes which result in their deposition and accumulation. Additionally, the material decumulation zone has a related synonym: decumulation zone.",4,True
:has_definition ""A material accumulation zone in which the rates of ice formation processes exceed those of ice decumulation processes, leading to a net icrease in some mass of ice.""

,The ice accumulation zone is identified as an intersection of a material accumulation zone and an area that at least overlaps some ice mass. It is classified as a type of material accumulation zone and also as a type of zone that at least contains processes of ice gain and overlaps some ice mass. The ice accumulation zone is defined as a material accumulation zone where the rates of ice formation processes surpass those of ice decumulation processes, resulting in a net increase in the mass of ice. Furthermore, the ice accumulation zone is broadly synonymous with the term ""accumulation area"" and has exact synonyms including ""area of ice gain,"" ""ice accumulation area,"" ""ice gain zone,"" and ""zone of ice gain.""",10,True
:has_definition ""A material decumulation zone in which the rates of ice formation processes are below those of ice decumulation processes, leading to a net decrease in some mass of ice.""

,The ice decumulation zone is characterized by several aspects that collectively define its nature and function. Primarily, it is identified as a type of material decumulation zone, emphasizing its role in the broader category of areas where material, in this case, ice, is being reduced. Furthermore, it is specifically described as a zone where processes leading to ice loss are at least present, indicating that its defining characteristic involves some form of ice reduction activity. The detailed definition provided for the ice decumulation zone further clarifies its nature: it is a material decumulation zone where the rates of ice formation are outpaced by the rates of ice decumulation, resulting in a net decrease in ice mass. This highlights the dynamic processes at play, emphasizing the imbalance between ice formation and loss.

In addition to its functional and definitional characteristics, the ice decumulation zone is also known by several exact synonyms that help in understanding its essence and implications more broadly. These synonyms include ""area of ice loss,"" ""ice decumulation area,"" ""ice loss zone,"" and ""zone of ice loss."" Each of these terms reinforces the fundamental aspect of the zone's purpose and effect - the reduction or loss of ice within a specified area. Collectively, these descriptors and synonyms provide a comprehensive understanding of what an ice decumulation zone is and its significance in the context of ice dynamics and environmental studies.",7,True
:has_definition ""An ice accumulation zone which overlaps part of a glacier.""

,The glacial ice accumulation zone is a specific type of ice accumulation zone, characterized by processes that involve some degree of glacial ice gain and at least partially overlaps with a glacier. It is defined as an ice accumulation zone that overlaps part of a glacier. Additionally, it is broadly synonymous with the term ""accumulation area"" and has several exact synonyms, including the ""area of glacial ice gain,"" ""glacial ice accumulation area,"" ""glacial ice gain zone,"" and the ""zone of glacial ice gain.""",9,True
:has_definition ""An environmental zone in which the rates of two or more processes are roughly equal to one another."" .

,The environmental zone of processual equilibrium is a type of environmental zone, which is characterized as a type of entity that at least contains some environmental system process. It is defined as an environmental zone in which the rates of two or more processes are roughly equal to one another.",3,True
:has_definition ""A glacier which is contained in the site bounded by a volcanic crater.""

,A volcanic crater glacier is a type of glacier that is at least contained in some volcanic crater zone. It is defined as a glacier which is contained in the site bounded by a volcanic crater. Additionally, a volcanic crater glacier is also known by its related synonym, crater glacier.",4,True
:has_definition ""The site which is located in a crater."" .

,The crater zone is a type of environmental zone characterized by its location within a crater, meaning it is at least partially surrounded by some crater. It is defined as the site which is located in a crater.",3,True
:has_definition ""The site which is located in a volcanic crater."" .

,A volcanic crater zone is a type of crater zone and is also a type of zone that is at least partially surrounded by some volcanic crater. Furthermore, it is defined as the site which is located in a volcanic crater.",3,True
:has_definition ""A landform which has been rendered barren or partially barren by environmental extremes, especially by low rainfall."" .

,A desert is a type of surface landform and also a type of something that at least overlaps some desert area. It is defined as a landform which has been rendered barren or partially barren by environmental extremes, especially by low rainfall.",3,True
:has_definition ""A climate which is realised through hydrological processes."" .

,Hydroclimate is a type of climate and is also a type of something that is at least realized in some hydrological process. It is defined as a climate which is realized through hydrological processes.,3,True

:has_broad_synonym ""rapid formation of liquid or solid particles from gaseous material in an atmosphere""
:has_definition ""An aerosol formation event  which occurs in an atmosphere."" .

,An atmospheric aerosolised particle formation event is both a type of aerosolised particle formation event and a type of atmospheric process. It is equivalent to something that represents the intersection of an aerosolised particle formation event and an occurrence that at least happens in some atmosphere. This event is defined as an aerosol formation event which occurs in an atmosphere and is broadly synonymous with the rapid formation of liquid or solid particles from gaseous material in an atmosphere.,5,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001360,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""An alpine tundra ecosystem which exists above the continuous timberline but below the permanent snowline on elevated land in tropical regions."" .

,Paramo is a type of alpine tundra ecosystem and also a type of tropical environment. It is characterized by being a type of environment that includes areas with soil that intersects with areas having at least some increased acidity. Moreover, paramo is defined as an alpine tundra ecosystem that exists above the continuous timberline but below the permanent snowline on elevated land in tropical regions.",4,True
:has_definition ""A direction which inheres in an atmospheric wind, typically expressed as the inverse of the direction the wind is moving in."" .

,Atmospheric wind direction is a type of direction and also a type of characteristic that at least some atmospheric winds possess. It shares the same definition as something that intersects with a direction and a characteristic that at least some atmospheric winds have. Moreover, atmospheric wind direction is defined as a direction which inheres in an atmospheric wind, typically expressed as the inverse of the direction the wind is moving in.",4,True

,Atmospheric wind speed is a type of speed defined as the speed of an atmospheric wind. It has broad synonyms including flow velocity of wind, speed of wind, wind flow velocity, and wind speed. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: speed of atmospheric wind.",7,True
:has_definition ""The volume of water which has fallen during a precipitation process.""

,The volume of hydrological precipitation is defined as the volume of water that has fallen during a precipitation process, and it is synonymous with Niederschlagsmenge and precipitation amount. It also has related synonyms such as precipitation, precipitation level, and precipitation quantity. This concept is categorized as a type of volume and shares characteristics with substances that intersect the category of liquid water and those that derive from the output of some hydrological precipitation process. Specifically, it is equivalent to something that intersects the domain of substances with volume and those that possess at least one characteristic of entities found within the intersection of liquid water and derivatives of hydrological precipitation outputs.",9,True
:has_definition ""A system which consists of an atmosphere, hydrosphere, cryosphere, land surface, and  biosphere, forced or influenced by external processes."" .

,The climate system is a type of ecosystem and a specific instance of something that at least partially comprises an intersection involving the atmosphere, planetary landmass, biosphere, hydrosphere, and cryosphere. Moreover, the climate system is defined as a system that consists of an atmosphere, hydrosphere, cryosphere, land surface, and biosphere, which are forced or influenced by external processes.",3,True

""formation of an aerosol in an atmosphere"",
""formation of an aerosol in the atmosphere"",

,The atmospheric secondary aerosol formation process is defined as a process during which gas-phase molecules form solid or liquid particles that are stable enough to continue growing in size - via the condensation or aggregation of other gas-phase molecules - at a greater rate than their constituents re-enter gas phase. This process is both a type of secondary aerosol formation process and a type of atmospheric process. It is synonymous with the formation of liquid or solid particles from gaseous material in an atmosphere, atmospheric formation of an aerosol, formation of an aerosol in an atmosphere, formation of an aerosol in the atmosphere, and formation of particles from gaseous material in an atmosphere. Furthermore, it is equivalent to something that is at the intersection of something that is a secondary aerosol formation process and something that at least occurs in some atmosphere.",9,True

:has_definition ""A process during which particles suspended in a gaseous medium are formed.""

,The aerosolised particle formation process is a type of particulate matter formation process, which is part of the aerosol formation process. It involves a process during which particles suspended in a gaseous medium are formed and is also known as the new particle formation process. This process is characterized by the union of materials that possess some quality of a solid and some quality of a liquid, ultimately resulting in the output of some particulate environmental material. Additionally, it requires some gaseous environmental material as input.",6,True
:has_definition ""A material transport process during which solid or liquid particles are directly introduced into a volume of gas.""

,The primary aerosol formation process is equivalent to a phenomenon that intersects a material transport process with a process that necessarily inputs materials at the crossroads of gaseous environmental materials and a combined set of particulate, solid, and liquid environmental materials. Additionally, this process is mandated to output aerosols. It is categorized as a specific kind of material transport process and is also defined as a process that essentially requires the input of materials that are a blend of gaseous environmental materials with a mix of particulate, solid, and liquid environmental materials. Furthermore, the primary aerosol formation process is recognized as a process that invariably results in the production of aerosols. It is described as a material transport process during which solid or liquid particles are directly introduced into a volume of gas. This process is alternatively known as primary aerosol formation.",6,True

:has_definition ""An aerosol formation process during which solid or liquid particles are either 1) formed in a volume of gas through gas-to-liquid or gas-to-solid conversions or 2) increase in size through aggregation with other particles.""

,The secondary aerosol formation process is categorized as an environmental system process and is a specific type of process that encompasses at least some parts that are a combination of aerosolized particle formation process and accumulation of matter on aerosolized particles. This process is defined as an aerosol formation process during which solid or liquid particles are either 1) formed in a volume of gas through gas-to-liquid or gas-to-solid conversions or 2) increase in size through aggregation with other particles. Additionally, the secondary aerosol formation process is exactly synonymous with secondary aerosol formation.",4,True

:has_definition ""A shrubland biome which is densely vegetated by dwarf or short mangroves (and associates) that are generally less than 6 meters in height, is tidally influenced,  is located in tropical or subtropical areas."" .

,Tidal mangrove shrubland is characterized as a type of shrubland biome that encapsulates several unique features and compositions. It is acknowledged for having at least a portion of its area covered by the mangrove biome and intersects with an ecological community predominantly composed of Laguncularia racemosa, Salicornia pacifica, Avicennia germinans, and Batis maritima. This biome is notably affected by tidal flow processes and possesses qualities that align it with both tropical and subtropical regions. Tidal mangrove shrubland is defined as a shrubland biome densely vegetated by dwarf or short mangroves, along with associated vegetation, where the trees generally do not exceed 6 meters in height. This biome is influenced by tidal movements and is situated in areas classified as either tropical or subtropical.",6,True

:has_definition ""An ecosystem which 1) typically has monthly average temperatures below 10 degrees Celsius 2) has a low evapotranspiration ratio 3) is dominated by treeless terrain, covered by communities of low-growing vegetation such as dwarf shrubs, sedges and grasses, mosses, and lichens, 4) contains areas of soil underlain by permafrost with a thin active layer and 5) occurs in both polar and alpine regions (i.e., both high latitudes and high altitudes), and 5) does not have permanent snow or ice cover.""^^xsd:string .

,The tundra ecosystem is a type of terrestrial ecosystem characterized by several key features. Firstly, it includes areas where the soil intersects with qualities of being frozen, indicating the presence of permafrost or similar conditions. Additionally, the tundra ecosystem overlaps with regions identified as tundra areas, suggesting a geographical alignment with tundra landscapes. The definition of a tundra ecosystem encompasses an ecosystem that typically experiences monthly average temperatures below 10 degrees Celsius and has a low evapotranspiration ratio. It is recognized for its treeless terrain, which is covered by communities of low-growing vegetation such as dwarf shrubs, sedges and grasses, mosses, and lichens. Furthermore, the tundra ecosystem is marked by areas of soil underlain by permafrost, which includes a thin active layer. This type of ecosystem can be found in both polar and alpine regions, which means it occurs at high latitudes as well as high altitudes. Importantly, it does not maintain a permanent cover of snow or ice.",4,True
:has_definition ""A tundra ecosystem which exists at high altitudes and where vegetation is stunted due to low temperatures and high winds.""^^xsd:string .

,The Alpine tundra ecosystem is a specific type of tundra ecosystem and also a kind of entity that possesses some qualities of alpine, as well as sharing some overlap with areas of alpine tundra. It is defined as a tundra ecosystem that is found at high altitudes, characterized by stunted vegetation resulting from low temperatures and high winds.",4,True
:has_definition ""An aerosol formation process during which the rate of particle formation exceeds that which is normally present in the site of its occurrence."" .

,An aerosolised particle formation event is the same as an intersection of an aerosolised particle formation process and something that has at least some increased rate. It is a type of aerosolised particle formation process and also a type of something that at least has a quality of some increased rate. Additionally, an aerosolised particle formation event is defined as an aerosol formation process during which the rate of particle formation exceeds that which is normally present in the site of its occurrence.",4,True
:has_broad_synonym ""rapid formation of liquid or solid particles from gaseous material in an atmosphere""
:has_definition ""A secondary aerosol formation process which occurs in an atmosphere at an increased rate relative to background processes of the same kind.""

,A secondary atmospheric aerosol formation event is a type of secondary aerosol formation process, defined as a secondary aerosol formation process that occurs in an atmosphere at an increased rate relative to background processes of the same kind. It is broadly synonymous with the rapid formation of liquid or solid particles from gaseous material in an atmosphere and is also relatedly referred to as an atmospheric new particle formation event.",4,True

:has_definition ""A physical quality which inheres in a marine water body by virtue of the height, wavelength, period, and directional energy flux of its waves which evolve into swell through nonlinear dynamics.""

,Sea state is a type of physical quality and also a type of characteristic that is at least associated with some marine water body. It is defined as a physical quality which inheres in a marine water body by virtue of the height, wavelength, period, and directional energy flux of its waves, which evolve into swell through nonlinear dynamics. Additionally, sea state has an exact synonym: ocean state.",4,True
:has_definition ""A variability quality which inheres in sea ice, particularly in its concentration, area and extent, type, motion, deformation, age, thickness, and volume."" .

,Sea ice variability is characterized by a specific type of variability, one that is inherent in sea ice, particularly in aspects such as its concentration, area, extent, type, motion, deformation, age, thickness, and volume. This defines sea ice variability as a quality of variability that is at least a characteristic of some sea ice.",3,True

:has_definition ""A marine bed which is covered by animals which have benthic habitats, including attached, clinging, sessile, infaunal, burrowing, laying, interstitial, and slow-moving animals, but not animals that have created substrate."" .

,A marine faunal bed is a type of marine bed and also a type of entity that includes at least a part that is an intersection of an ecological community and entities composed primarily of metazoa. It is defined as a marine bed that is covered by animals with benthic habitats, which include attached, clinging, sessile, infaunal, burrowing, laying, interstitial, and slow-moving animals, but excludes animals that have created substrate. Furthermore, a marine faunal bed is broadly synonymous with a faunal bed.",4,True

:has_definition ""A elevation quality which inheres in a marine water body by virtue of the position of that water body's surface layer (adjacent to an atmosphere) relative to some reference elevation."" .

,Sea surface height is a type of elevation and is characteristic of some sea surface layer. It is defined as an elevation quality which inheres in a marine water body by virtue of the position of that water body's surface layer (adjacent to an atmosphere) relative to some reference elevation.,3,True

:has_definition ""A submerged bed which underlies a marine water body.""@en

,A marine bed is a type of submerged bed that is at least adjacent to some marine water body, and it is defined as a submerged bed which underlies a marine water body. Additionally, it has a narrow synonym: sea bottom.",4,True

:has_definition ""A marine faunal bed which is dominated by mussels of the Mytilus or Modiolus genera either 1) resting on the sediment surface, 2)  partially embedded in the sediment, 3) attached to conspecifics (by using their byssal threads), or 4) attached to a piece of gravel in slightly gravelly fine sediments."" .
,A mussel bed is a type of marine faunal bed that is characterized by its relation to the sediment surface
column2: it is either resting on it or partially embedded within it. Furthermore, a mussel bed is part of an ecological community primarily composed of organisms from the Modiolus and Mytilidae families, indicating its ecological significance and composition. The definition of a mussel bed elaborates on its nature as a marine faunal bed dominated by mussels from the Mytilus or Modiolus genera. These mussels can be found in various positions: resting on the sediment surface, partially embedded in the sediment, attached to conspecifics using their byssal threads, or attached to a piece of gravel in slightly gravelly fine sediments, highlighting the diverse nature of mussel bed environments.",4,True

column1: :has_definition ""A marine reef which is located on a shelf (i.e. in the neritic zone) and primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells."" .
,A neritic mussel reef is a type of mussel reef defined as a marine reef located on a shelf (i.e., in the neritic zone) and primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells.",2,True
:has_definition ""A marine reef which is present in the depths beyond (offshore relative to) the continental shelf and primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells."" .

,An Oceanic Mussel Reef is a type of Mussel Reef, which is a part of a union encompassing the Marine Bathyal Zone Biome, Marine Abyssal Zone Biome, and Marine Hadal Zone Biome. It is defined as a marine reef present in the depths beyond the continental shelf, primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells. Additionally, Oceanic Mussel Reef is alternatively termed Oceanic Mussel Reef Substrate.",4,True

:has_definition ""An area which is dominated by dense accumulations of mussels attached to a substrate other than conspecifics, including the associated faunal communities and predators present on the mussels (e.g., starfish)."" .

,The area of attached mussel assemblages is recognized as a type of marine environmental zone, an area of attached faunal communities, and a part of the marine benthic biome. It is also identified as overlapping with areas that are a union of mussel beds and mussel reefs. The definition of the area of attached mussel assemblages is an area dominated by dense accumulations of mussels attached to substrates other than conspecifics, inclusive of the associated faunal communities and predators present on the mussels, such as starfish. Furthermore, the area of attached mussel assemblages is alternatively termed as ""attached mussels"" within the biotic group.",6,True

:has_definition ""An area which is dominated by dense accumulations of mussels, of the genus Modiolus, attached to a substrate other than conspecifics, including the associated faunal communities and predators present on the mussels (e.g., starfish)."" .

,The area of attached modiolus assemblages represents a specific type within the broader category of area of attached mussel assemblages. Furthermore, this area is part of a category that encompasses elements from the marine bathyal zone biome, marine abyssal zone biome, and marine hadal zone biome. The area of attached modiolus assemblages is defined as an area characterized by dense accumulations of mussels from the genus Modiolus, which are attached to substrates other than their conspecifics. This definition also includes the associated faunal communities and predators present on the mussels, such as starfish.",3,True
:has_definition ""An environmental zone within which ecological communities of  animals are attached to some substrate."" .

,The area of attached faunal communities is a type of environmental zone and also a type of zone that at least overlaps with an intersection of an ecological community that is composed primarily of metazoa. Furthermore, the area of attached faunal communities is defined as an environmental zone within which ecological communities of animals are attached to some substrate.",3,True
:has_definition ""An oceanic mussel reef which is primarily settled by mussels of the genus Bathymodiolus and primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells"" .

,A Bathymodiolus-dominated oceanic mussel reef is a type of oceanic mussel reef characterized by its significant composition of mussels from the genus Bathymodiolus. It can also be defined as an oceanic mussel reef that is primarily settled by Bathymodiolus mussels and mainly composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells. Furthermore, this type of reef is a part of an ecological community and is at least composed primarily of Bathymodiolus. An alternative term for the Bathymodiolus-dominated oceanic mussel reef is the Bathymodiolus-dominated oceanic mussel reef substrate.",4,True
:has_definition ""A marine reef which is primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells."" .

,Mussel reef is a type of marine reef that falls under at least part of some continental shelf and is also a part of the marine neritic benthic zone biome. Furthermore, it is defined as a marine reef primarily composed of self-adhered or conglomerated mussel shells and has an alternative term, ""mussel reef substrate."" Additionally, a mussel reef is a type of ecological community that is at least composed primarily of a union of Modiolus and Mytilus, indicating its biological composition.",6,True
:has_definition ""A mussel bed which is located in benthic regions beyond (offshore to) a continental shelf."" .

,An oceanic mussel bed is a type of mussel bed that falls under the category of environments which are part of the union of marine bathyal zone biome, marine abyssal zone biome, and marine hadal zone biome. It is defined as a mussel bed located in benthic regions beyond (offshore to) a continental shelf.",3,True
:has_definition ""A mussel bed which is located in benthic regions that are part of a continental shelf."" .

,A neritic mussel bed is a type of mussel bed that is situated in benthic regions part of a continental shelf. This type of mussel bed is also considered a part of something within the marine neritic benthic zone biome. Specifically, it is defined as a mussel bed located in benthic regions that are part of a continental shelf.",3,True
:has_definition ""An oceanic mussel bed which has mussel communities dominated by members of the genus Bathymodiolus."" .

,A Bathymodiolus dominated oceanic mussel bed is a specific type of oceanic mussel bed, which is characterized by being a part of an ecological community that is primarily composed of the genus Bathymodiolus. Furthermore, a Bathymodiolus dominated oceanic mussel bed is defined as an oceanic mussel bed with mussel communities that are predominantly made up of members of the genus Bathymodiolus.",3,True

,Gill tissue material is a type of organic material. It is also a type of material that is at least composed primarily of something that is both a tissue and at least partly part of a gill.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001392,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

,Mussel gill tissue material is a type of gill tissue material that is at least composed primarily of tissues that are part of the intersection of something identified as tissue and something that is at least part of an intersection involving gills and something that is at least part of Mytilidae.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001393,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

,Bathymodiolus gill tissue material is a type of mussel gill tissue material. It is also a kind of material that is primarily composed of tissue that intersects with a component which is at least partially part of an entity that intersects with gill and is at least partially part of Bathymodiolus.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001394,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

,The accumulation of matter on aerosolized particles is recognized as a type of material accumulation process. This process is also identified as a type of phenomenon that at least involves, in part, a union of processes that include both condensation and desublimation. Furthermore, the accumulation of matter on aerosolized particles is characterized as a type of event that necessarily involves aerosols as participants.",3,True
:has_definition ""Biomass which is composed primarily of dead organisms, their parts, or their organic derivatives.""

,Necromass is a type of organic material, which is defined as biomass composed primarily of dead organisms, their parts, or their organic derivatives. Furthermore, necromass is exactly synonymous with both dead biological matter and dead biomass.",4,True
:has_definition ""Clay which is part of an abyssal plain."" .

,Abyssal clay is a type of clay and is part of at least some abyssal plains. It is defined as clay which is part of an abyssal plain.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001397,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

:has_definition ""A soil which has high mineral content and which contain no calcareous material, have less than 10% weatherable minerals its surface layer, and have less than 35% base saturation throughout its volume.""

,Ultisol is a type of soil that is characterized by having a high mineral content and lacking calcareous material. It contains less than 10% weatherable minerals in its surface layer and has less than 35% base saturation throughout its volume. This type of soil also has an increased mass as part of its composition, featuring a significant intersection with minerals. Additionally, Ultisol is exactly synonymous with red clay soil.",4,True
:has_definition ""A primary aerosol formation process during which dust particles are suspended in a gaseous medium."" .

,Aerosolisation of dust is a primary aerosol formation process which involves dust particles being suspended in a gaseous medium, defined specifically as a process during which dust serves as an input. The output of this process is a substance that is both dust and at least partly comprised of gaseous environmental material.",4,True
:has_definition ""A process during which dust is aerosolised in an atmosphere.""

,Atmospheric aerosolisation of dust is a type of aerosolisation of dust and also a type of atmospheric process. It is defined as a process during which dust is aerosolised in an atmosphere and has an exact synonym, ""dust event.""",4,True

:has_definition ""An aeroform which is formed as a result of strong upper winds spreading a cirrus homogenitus cloud in the atmosphere and, in turn, causing internal tranformations which result in the cloud taking on the appearnce of natural cirri-form clouds."" .

,Homomutatus cloud is a type of water-based cloud and something that at least derives from some cirrus homogenitus cloud. It is defined as an aeroform which is formed as a result of strong upper winds spreading a cirrus homogenitus cloud in the atmosphere and, in turn, causing internal transformations which result in the cloud taking on the appearance of natural cirri-form clouds.",3,True
:has_definition ""An environmental process during which a haze is formed by the aerosolisation of solid particles, including natural materials and anthropogenic pollutants, in an atmosphere."" .

,The haze formation process is identified as an atmospheric process that encompasses both primary and secondary aerosol formation processes as integral parts. It involves inputs that are at the intersection of particulate environmental materials, which possess qualities of being solid and dry. Additionally, the process results in the production of haze as an output. Defined more comprehensively, the haze formation process is an environmental phenomenon where haze is generated through the aerosolization of solid particles. These particles include a range of materials from natural origins to anthropogenic pollutants present in the atmosphere.",6,True
:has_definition ""An aersolised mass of dust, smoke, or other dry particulates which scatters visible light thus obsscuring visibility through an atmosphere."" .

,Haze is a type of aerosolised solids and also a type of atmospheric aerosol. It is composed primarily of a combination of dust and smoke, as well as the intersection of aerosolised solids and substances that are dry. Haze is defined as an aerosolised mass of dust, smoke, or other dry particulates which scatters visible light, thereby obscuring visibility through an atmosphere.",4,True
:has_definition ""A haze formation process which has an increased rate relative to that which is usually present in a given site."" .

,A haze formation event is a type of haze formation process that is characterized by having at least some quality of an increased rate. Specifically, it is defined as a haze formation process which has an increased rate relative to that which is usually present in a given site.",3,True

:has_definition ""An ecosystem which is of larger scale than an ecoregion and which includes smaller ecosystems determined by the presence of ecological assemblages that have at least some cohesion over evolutionary time frames."" .

,An ecological province is a type of ecosystem that is characterized as a larger scale ecosystem than an ecoregion and includes smaller ecosystems. These smaller ecosystems are determined by the presence of ecological assemblages that exhibit at least some cohesion over evolutionary time frames. Additionally, an ecological province is defined as a type of entity that encompasses at least a part of some ecoregion.",3,True

:has_definition ""An anthropogenic environment which is bounded by the building envelope of a laboratory and in which a system of manufactured products exert control on one or more of its environmental conditions."" .

,A laboratory environment is a type of anthropogenic environment, defined as an anthropogenic environment which is bounded by the building envelope of a laboratory. In this environment, a system of manufactured products exerts control on one or more of its environmental conditions.",2,True

:has_definition ""A research facility in which systems of manufactured products control internal conditions and in which scientific or technological research, experiments, and measurement may be performed.""

,A laboratory facility is a type of research facility and is also considered a type of entity that must include at least some part of a laboratory environment. It is defined as a research facility in which systems of manufactured products control internal conditions, and where scientific or technological research, experiments, and measurement can be conducted. Furthermore, a laboratory facility is exactly synonymous with a research laboratory.",4,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) has been shaped into structural elements resembling grains or ripples, 2) is almost exclusively composed of ice crystals, 3) is located in the high level of the atmosphere (high étage).""@en

,Cirrocumulus clouds are a type of cloud that exists as ice masses and are water-based. They are found at least partially within some high atmospheric levels and are primarily composed of an intersection of object aggregates and water ice crystals. The definition of a cirrocumulus cloud includes a cloud that has structural elements resembling grains or ripples, is almost exclusively composed of ice crystals, and is located in the high level of the atmosphere (high étage). Additionally, cirrocumulus clouds have exact synonyms, including Cirrocumulus-Wolke, Hohe Schäfchenwolke, and Zirrokumulus.",8,True
:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) occurs in the form of a smooth or fibrous veil, 2) is composed of few small ice crystals, 3) is located in the high level of the atmosphere (high étage).""@en

,A Cirrostratus cloud is a type of ice mass and a water-based cloud that exists as part of the high atmospheric level. It is primarily composed of an aggregate of objects that intersect with water ice crystals, which have a decreased size and amount. The definition of a Cirrostratus cloud is a cloud that occurs in the form of a smooth or fibrous veil, is composed of few small ice crystals, and is located in the high level of the atmosphere (high étage). Cirrostratus clouds are also exactly synonymous with Cirrostratus, Hohe Schleierwolke, and Zirrostratus.",8,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) has been shaped into laminae, rounded masses or rolls, 2) is exclusively composed of water droplets, 3) is located in the middle level of the atmosphere (middle étage).""@en

,The Altocumulus cloud is a type of water-based cloud, which is essentially a mass of liquid located within the middle atmospheric level. It possesses qualities such as being laminar and is primarily composed of liquid water. Furthermore, it is an intersection of an object aggregate and has members that include water droplets. The Altocumulus cloud is defined as a cloud characterized by its formation into laminae, rounded masses, or rolls, and its exclusive composition of water droplets, positioned in the middle level of the atmosphere (middle étage). In terms of nomenclature, it is precisely synonymous with ""Altocumulus-Wolke"" and ""Grobe Schäfchenwolke.""",9,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) occurs in the form of a striated, fibrous, or uniform sheet or layer, 2) is composed of water droplets and ice crystals, 3) is located in the middle level of the atmosphere (middle étage).""@en

,An Altostratus cloud is a type of water-based cloud that falls within the middle atmospheric level and possesses a laminar quality. It is primarily composed of an object aggregate intersecting with members that are either water droplets or water ice crystals. This cloud is defined as a cloud that occurs in the form of a striated, fibrous, or uniform sheet or layer, composed of water droplets and ice crystals, and is located in the middle level of the atmosphere (middle étage). Additionally, Altostratus cloud is exactly synonymous with ""Altostratus-Wolke"" and ""Mittelhohe Schichtwolke.""",7,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) occurs in the form of a layer, 2) is composed of water droplets (sometimes supercooled) and raindrops, or snow crystals and snowflakes, or of a mixture of these liquid and solid particles, 3) is located in the middle level of the atmosphere (middle étage).""@en

,The nimbostratus cloud is a type of water-based cloud that also falls within the middle atmospheric level, at least partially. It possesses laminar qualities and is primarily composed of an aggregate of objects which include water droplets, supercooled water droplets, and snow crystals. The nimbostratus cloud is defined as a cloud that appears as a layer, made up of water droplets (which can be supercooled), raindrops, or snow crystals and snowflakes, or a combination of these liquid and solid particles, and is situated in the middle level of the atmosphere (middle étage). Additionally, ""Nimbostratus-Wolke"" and ""Regen-schichtwolke"" are exact synonyms for the nimbostratus cloud.",7,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) has been shaped into non-fibrous tessellations, rounded masses, or rolls, 2) is primarily composed of water droplets, and may contain raindrops or, more rarely, snow pellets, snow crystals and snowflakes, 3) is located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage).""@en

,Stratocumulus cloud, known by its exact synonyms Haufenschichtwolke and Stratocumulus-Wolke, is a type of water-based cloud and mass of liquid. It is characterized by its location at least partially within some low atmospheric level and is primarily composed of liquid water. This type of cloud is essentially an aggregate of objects that include a mix of raindrops, water droplets, graupel, and snow crystals. Specifically, a stratocumulus cloud is defined as a cloud that 1) appears in non-fibrous tessellations, rounded masses, or rolls, 2) mainly consists of water droplets, and may contain raindrops, or more rarely, snow pellets, snow crystals, and snowflakes, 3) occupies the low level of the atmosphere, also known as the low étage.",8,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) occurs in the form of a layer with a fairly uniform base or, less frequently, ragged patches, 2) is composed of small water droplets, 3) is located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage).""@en

,Stratus clouds are a type of water-based cloud and mass of liquid that primarily consists of liquid water. These clouds form at least part of the low atmospheric level and are characterized by being at least partly composed of objects that intersect with the cloud base and have qualities that are either invariant or fringed. Additionally, stratus clouds are composed primarily of an aggregate of objects that include water droplets with decreased size. They are defined as clouds that occur in the form of a layer with a fairly uniform base or, less frequently, in ragged patches. These clouds are composed of small water droplets and are located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage). Stratus clouds are also known by their exact synonyms ""Stratus-Wolke"" and ""niedere Schichtwolke.""",9,True

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) has been shaped into rising mounds, domes, or towers with a bulging upper part resembling a cauliflower and a near horizontal or ragged base, 2) is mainly composed of water droplets, 3) is located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage).""@en

,A cumulus cloud is a type of water-based cloud that can also be described as a mass of liquid. It partially occupies the low atmospheric level and intersects with the cloud base, featuring characteristics that are both horizontal and fringed. Additionally, cumulus clouds possess a domed quality and are primarily composed of liquid water, including an aggregate of objects that notably contain water droplets. These clouds are defined as formations that have been shaped into rising mounds, domes, or towers with a bulging upper part resembling a cauliflower and a base that is either near horizontal or ragged. They are mainly composed of water droplets and are located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage). Cumulus clouds are also known by several exact synonyms, including Cumuluswolke, Haufenwolke, Kumuluswolke, and Quellwolke.",12,True
:has_definition ""A cloud which is formed by condensation events triggered by some anthropogenic processes or the outputs thereof, such as aircraft contrails or emissions from chimneys."" .

,A homogenitus cloud is the same as something that is both a water-based cloud and something that has at least formed as a result of some anthropogenic environmental process. It is a type of water-based cloud and also a type that forms as a result of anthropogenic environmental processes. The homogenitus cloud is defined as a cloud which forms through condensation events triggered by anthropogenic processes or their outputs, such as aircraft contrails or chimney emissions.",4,True
:has_definition ""A mining process during which materials are extracted from benthic environments deep below the ocean surface, where no stellar radiation reaches..""

,Benthic deep sea mining, also known as deep seafloor mining or deep-seafloor mining, is a specific type of marine mining. It is defined as a mining process during which materials are extracted from benthic environments deep below the ocean surface, areas devoid of stellar radiation. This form of mining intersects with marine mining and is particularly associated with regions that include or are a combination of the abyssal plain, deep marine sediment, marine bathyal zone biome, marine abyssal zone biome, and marine hadal zone biome.",6,True
:has_definition ""A cloud which develop locally over forests as a result of increased humidity due to evaporation and evapotranspiration from the tree canopy."" .

,Silvagenitus clouds are a type of water-based clouds that specifically form as a result of the intersection between evapotranspiration processes and forest ecosystems acting as the causal agents. These clouds develop locally over forests due to the increased humidity resulting from evaporation and evapotranspiration from the tree canopy.,4,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001418,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A cirrus cloud which occurs as a detached unit or a thin veil and consists of nearly straight or irregularly curved filaments that do not terminate in hooks or tufts."" .

,A cirrus fibratus cloud is a type of cirrus cloud that is characterized as a cirrus cloud which occurs either as a detached unit or a thin veil. It consists of nearly straight or irregularly curved filaments that do not terminate in hooks or tufts.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001419,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

:has_definition ""A cloud which 1) has been shaped into dense, mountain-like forms or one or more tower-like forms with a flattened upper portion, which often spreads out in the shape of an anvil or plume, 2) is composed of water droplets and, especially in its upper portion, ice crystals, 3) is located in the low level of the atmosphere (low étage), but can extend into the middle and high level of the atmosphere.""@en

,The Cumulonimbus cloud is a type of water-based cloud characterized by a number of distinctive features. Firstly, it spans across various atmospheric levels, including the low, middle, and high atmospheric levels. This cloud type is notable for its increased size and increased mass density. The structure of a Cumulonimbus cloud includes a top part that intersects with flat qualities, indicating that the cloud's upper portion is often flattened.

Compositionally, Cumulonimbus clouds are primarily made of an aggregate of objects that include both water droplets and water ice crystals. This indicates a complex structure that combines liquid and frozen forms of water, contributing to its dense and towering appearance.

A detailed definition of a Cumulonimbus cloud outlines it as a cloud that forms dense, mountain-like shapes or tower-like structures with a flattened upper part, which may spread out resembling an anvil or plume. In addition to being composed of water droplets, particularly in its lower parts, the cloud also contains ice crystals, especially in its upper portion. Despite originating in the low level of the atmosphere, a Cumulonimbus cloud has the capacity to extend into the middle and high atmospheric levels.

Moreover, the Cumulonimbus cloud is also known by exact synonyms ""Cumulonibus-Wolke"" and ""Gewitterwolke,"" reflecting its association with thunderstorm phenomena and its recognition in different languages.",9,True
:has_definition ""A mining process during which materials are extracted from the surface, or below the surface, of the ocean floor."" .

,Sea bed mining, which is a type of marine mining and also a type that involves at least some participation from the sea floor, is equivalent to the intersection of marine mining and activities that involve the sea floor. Furthermore, sea bed mining is defined as a mining process during which materials are extracted from the surface, or below the surface, of the ocean floor.",4,True

:has_definition ""A cirrus cloud which does not have grey parts and which is often shaped like a comma, terminating at its highest point in a hook, or in a tuft, the upper part of which is not in the form of a rounded protuberance."" .

,The cirrus uncinus cloud, a specific type of cirrus cloud, is defined as a cirrus cloud that lacks grey parts and frequently resembles a comma in shape, ending at its highest point with a hook or a tuft, where the upper part does not form a rounded protuberance.",2,True

:has_definition ""A cirrus cloud which 1) is structurally organised in patches, 2) is sufficiently dense to appear greyish when viewed towards the local star and 3) may veil, the local star, obscure its outline, or even hide it entirely."" .

,The cirrus spissatus cloud is a type of cirrus cloud. It is defined as a cirrus cloud that is structurally organized in patches and is sufficiently dense to appear greyish when viewed towards the local star. Moreover, it may veil the local star, obscure its outline, or even hide it entirely.",2,True
:has_definition ""A cirrostratus cloud which occurs as a detached unit or a thin veil and consists of nearly straight or irregularly curved filaments that do not terminate in hooks or tufts."" .

,The Cirrostratus fibratus cloud is a specific type of Cirrostratus cloud, defined as a Cirrostratus cloud that appears either as a detached unit or a thin veil. It is characterized by nearly straight or irregularly curved filaments, which notably do not terminate in hooks or tufts.",2,True

:has_definition ""A stratocumulus cloud which 1) has linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances which resemble crenellated turrets or towers, some of which are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts, 2) possess a lower region or base which connects these protuberances."" .

,The Stratocumulus Castellanus cloud is a type of Stratocumulus cloud defined by its distinctive features. Specifically, it displays linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances that resemble crenellated turrets or towers, with some protuberances being taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts. Additionally, this cloud type has a lower region or base that connects these protuberances.",2,True

:has_definition ""A cirrus cloud which 1) has linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances which resemble crenellated turrets or towers, some of which are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts, 2) possess a lower region or base which connects these protuberances."" .

,The Cirrus Castellanus cloud is a type of Cirrus cloud characterized by a unique structure. Its definition encompasses a Cirrus cloud that features linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances, resembling crenellated turrets or towers. Some of these protuberances are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts. Additionally, it possesses a lower region or base that connects these protuberances.",2,True

:has_definition ""A cirrocumulus cloud which 1) has linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances which resemble crenellated turrets or towers, some of which are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts, 2) possess a lower region or base which connects these protuberances."" .

,The cirrocumulus castellanus cloud is a specific type of cirrocumulus cloud. It is defined as a cirrocumulus cloud that features linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances, resembling crenellated turrets or towers. Some of these protuberances are taller than they are wide in some part of their upper sections. Additionally, it possesses a lower region or base that connects these protuberances.",2,True

:has_definition ""An altocumulus cloud which 1) has linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances which resemble crenellated turrets or towers, some of which are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts, 2) possess a lower region or base which connects these protuberances."" .

,The altocumulus castellanus cloud is a type of altocumulus cloud defined by its unique characteristics. It features linearly arranged cumuliform protuberances that resemble crenellated turrets or towers, some of which are taller than they are wide in some portion of their upper parts. Additionally, it possesses a lower region or base that connects these protuberances.",2,True
:has_definition ""A cloud which is primarily composed of water-based aerosols."" .

,Water-based clouds are a type of cloud, hydrometeor, and something that at least has part some water droplet. They are defined as clouds which are primarily composed of water-based aerosols. Additionally, water-based cloud has a broad synonym, which is cloud mass.",5,True

:has_definition ""An anthropisation process during which terrestrial environments - natural or anthropised - or parts thereof are altered to facilitate human activities such as agriculture, settlement, or commerce.""

,The land conversion process is categorized as a type of land consumption process, and it is also considered a type of process that involves at least some terrestrial biome as a participant. Furthermore, it is recognized as a type of process that involves participation from entities that are a union of anthropogenic environments and natural environments. The land conversion process is defined as an anthropisation process during which terrestrial environments - whether natural or anthropised - or parts thereof are altered to facilitate human activities such as agriculture, settlement, or commerce. Additionally, ""land conversion"" and ""land development"" are identified as exact synonyms for the land conversion process.",6,True
:has_definition ""A land conversion process during which terrestrial ecosystems are altered to facilitate agricultural activities such as crop cultivation or the rearing of livestock.""

,The agricultural land conversion process is a type of land conversion process and is also exactly synonymous with agricultural land conversion. It is characterized as a process where terrestrial ecosystems are modified to support agricultural activities, including the cultivation of crops or livestock rearing. Furthermore, this process is a subset of processes that yield outputs intersecting with agricultural fields, cropland biomes, village biomes, and rangeland biomes.",4,True
:has_definition ""An anthropogenic environmental process which includes all human activities undertaken in a natural, semi-natural, or anthropised environment."" .

,The land use process is identical to an intersection involving a planned environmental usage process and entities that at least have a participant from a group consisting of terrestrial biomes, planetary landmasses, and terrestrial natural environments. Additionally, the land use process falls under the category of planned environmental usage processes. It is also categorized under processes that at least have a part from a group including land consumption processes, land conversion processes, and land degradation. Furthermore, the land use process is classified under processes that have at least one participant from a collective of terrestrial biomes, planetary landmasses, and terrestrial natural environments. The land use process is defined as an anthropogenic environmental process encompassing all human activities carried out in natural, semi-natural, or anthropised environments.",5,True

:has_definition ""A land use process during which humans access and manage forest ecosystems for 1) the provisioning of wood, forages, water, wildlife, and recreation as well as a broad range of other ecosystem services or 2) the maintenance of the forest ecosystem's health."" .

,Forestry is a type of land use process, defined as a land use process during which humans access and manage forest ecosystems. This management aims for the provisioning of wood, forages, water, wildlife, and recreation, as well as a broad range of other ecosystem services, or for the maintenance of the forest ecosystem's health.",2,True
:has_definition ""A land use process during which materials of economic value are extracted from a planet, usually from an orebody, lode, vein, seam, reef or placer deposit."" .

,Terrestrial mining is the same as something that intersects mining and something that has at least one participant, which is either a terrestrial biome, planetary landmass, or terrestrial natural environment. It is a type of land use process and also a type of mining. Terrestrial mining is defined as a land use process during which materials of economic value are extracted from a planet, usually from an ore body, lode, vein, seam, reef, or placer deposit.
