Additionally, terrestrial mining has a broad synonym: mining.",5,True
:has_definition ""A process during which an ecosystem - natural or anthropised - is changed by the actions of humans."" .

,The anthropogenic ecosystem conversion process is a type of anthropogenic environmental process defined as a process during which an ecosystem, whether natural or anthropised, is changed by the actions of humans.",2,True
:has_definition ""Deforestation which is planned and executed by humans."" .

,Planned deforestation is defined as deforestation which is planned and executed by humans, and it represents the intersection of a process that is both a form of deforestation and a realization of a plan specification. It is categorized as a type of deforestation, as well as a type of anthropogenic environmental process. Additionally, planned deforestation is recognized as an instance that realizes a plan specification.",5,True
:has_definition ""A planned process during which humans access and obtain resources, benefits, or services from a natural or anthropised ecosystem."" .

,A planned environmental usage process is categorized as a type of anthropogenic environmental process, a type of planned process, and also a type that involves at least some part of an active ecosystem management process. Additionally, it is defined as a type that includes participants from a union of anthropogenic and natural environments. The planned environmental usage process is defined as a planned process during which humans access and obtain resources, benefits, or services from a natural or anthropized ecosystem.",5,True
:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which a non-renewable resource such as petroleum, natural gas, or water is extracted from an ecosystem."" .

,Mining is a type of planned environmental usage process that involves at least some material extraction and ecosystem fragmentation processes. It is defined as a process during which a non-renewable resource such as petroleum, natural gas, or water is extracted from an ecosystem.",4,True
:has_definition ""A mining process during which rock or mineral deposits are extracted from the terrestrial surface layers of an astronomical body."" .
,Quarrying, a type of terrestrial mining, is defined as a mining process during which rock or mineral deposits are extracted from the terrestrial surface layers of an astronomical body.",2,True
:has_definition ""A mining process which occurs in a marine ecosystem."" .

,Marine mining is a type of mining that is equivalent to an activity that intersects mining with an entity that involves at least one participant from the union of marine biomes and marine environments. Furthermore, marine mining is characterized as a type of activity that necessitates at least one participant from either marine biomes or marine environments. Additionally, marine mining is defined as a mining process that occurs within a marine ecosystem.",4,True
:has_definition ""A mining process during which coal is extracted from the rocky portion of an astronomical body."" .

,Coal mining is a type of mining which is defined as a mining process during which coal is extracted from the rocky portion of an astronomical body. It involves at least some coal mines and coal as participants. Moreover, coal mining results in the production of coal mine waste material.",5,True

:has_definition ""A mining process during which metal ores and minerals that lie near the terrestrial surface of an astronomical body are extracted by removing the overlying material and breaking and loading the ore.""

,Opencast mining, which is a type of terrestrial mining, is defined as a mining process during which metal ores and minerals that lie near the terrestrial surface of an astronomical body are extracted by removing the overlying material and breaking and loading the ore. Furthermore, opencast mining is exactly synonymous with both open-pit mining and strip mining.",4,True

:has_definition ""A land use process during which terrestrial environments are modified such that they can grow crop plants or allow the rearing of animals to provide food, fiber, medicines, or other products used by humans."" .

,Agriculture is a type of land use process defined as a land use process during which terrestrial environments are modified such that they can grow crop plants or allow the rearing of animals to provide food, fiber, medicines, or other products used by humans.",2,True

:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which humans access an environment in order to promote the refreshment of their physical and psychological health through relaxation and leisure activities."" .

,The usage of an environment for recreation is a type of planned environmental usage process, which is defined as a planned process during which humans access an environment to promote the refreshment of their physical and psychological health through relaxation and leisure activities. Additionally, this concept is broadly synonymous with both ""leisure"" and ""recreation.""",4,True

:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment facilitates the movement of materials and material objects (persons or goods) from place to place, typically with the assistance of a vehicle."" .

,The usage of an environment for transportation is defined as a planned environmental usage process where an environment facilitates the movement of materials and material objects, such as persons or goods, from one place to another, typically with the assistance of a vehicle. This type of usage is also characterized by being part of a process that involves the transportation of materials and necessitates the participation of transport features. Additionally, the term ""usage of an environment for transportation"" is broadly synonymous with ""transportation.""",5,True

:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports 1) enterprises concerned with the provision to the public of essentials, such as electricity or water or 2) the basic network or foundation of capital facilities or community investments which are necessary to support economic and community activities."" .

,The usage of an environment for infrastructure and utilities is categorized as a planned environmental usage process, which inherently includes at least a part of some material transport process and involves some transport feature as a participant. This process is defined as a scenario during which the environment aids enterprises in providing essential services to the public, such as electricity or water, or supports the basic network and foundation of capital facilities or community investments crucial for economic and community activities. Furthermore, this type of environmental usage is broadly synonymous with transportation.",5,True
:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports the settlement and dwelling of a community of humans."" .

,The usage of an environment for residential activity is classified as a planned environmental usage process, which inherently involves the settlement and dwelling of a community of humans. This process is not only a type of activity that includes human dwelling as a participant but also encompasses the intersection of an ecological community primarily composed of Homo sapiens. Furthermore, this specific usage of an environment is broadly synonymous with ""residential,"" defining it as a process during which an environment supports the settlement and dwelling of a human community.",5,True
:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports welfare activities organised by the state or a local authority and carried out by trained personnel."" .

,The usage of an environment for community and social services is a type of planned environmental usage process, which is defined as a process during which an environment supports welfare activities organized by the state or a local authority and carried out by trained personnel. This type of usage is also categorized as something that involves participants that are at the intersection of an ecological community and entities composed primarily of Homo sapiens.",3,True
:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports the sale of goods to ultimate consumers, usually in small quantities."" .

,The usage of an environment for retail activity is categorized as a type of planned environmental usage process. This process is defined as a planned environmental usage during which an environment facilitates the sale of goods to ultimate consumers, typically in small quantities.",2,True

:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports activities which aim to protect citizens or any geographical area by preparing for or by using military means to resist the attack of an enemy."" .

,The usage of an environment for defense is categorized as a type of planned environmental usage process. This process is defined as a scenario during which an environment aids activities that are focused on safeguarding citizens or any geographical area. This is accomplished by preparing for or employing military strategies to counteract an enemy's assault.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001450,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports manufacturing facilities producing commodities that are sold with the expectation of recovering the total cost of production."" .

,The usage of an environment for industry is characterized as a planned environmental usage process. This type of usage involves at least one participant, specifically some industrial building, and results in the output of some industrial waste material. Furthermore, the usage of an environment for industry is defined as a process during which an environment supports manufacturing facilities. These facilities are engaged in producing commodities that are sold with the expectation of recovering the total cost of production.",4,True

:has_definition ""A planned environmental usage process during which an environment supports facilities associated with commerce or the earning of a livelihood through means other than manufacturing or the provision of a public service."" .

,The usage of an environment for business is defined as a planned environmental usage process. During this process, an environment supports facilities associated with commerce or the earning of a livelihood through means other than manufacturing or the provision of a public service.",2,True
:has_definition ""A habitat which supports the persistence and growth of a population of Calyptra moths and which overlaps mesic meadows and edges and clearings in vegetated areas.""

,The Calyptra habitat is defined as a type of habitat that supports the persistence and growth of a population of Calyptra moths. It is primarily composed of and determined by an intersection of the population of organisms and areas that support Calyptra. This habitat overlaps with mesic meadows and edges and clearings in vegetated areas. Furthermore, the Calyptra habitat is exactly synonymous with the term ""vampire moth habitat.""",4,True
:has_definition ""A mountain which is located on land and which is bounded by an atmosphere or outer space."" .

,A terrestrial mountain is categorized as a type of mountain that is not only situated on a planetary landmass but is also encompassed by a region that represents the intersection of the landmass with a zone that constitutes the union of the atmosphere and outer space. Furthermore, it is defined as a mountain located on land and bounded by an atmosphere or outer space.",3,True
:has_definition ""A mountain that is part of a polar environment.""^^xsd:string .

,Polar Mountain is a type of mountain that falls under a category which includes at least a part of entities that are either part of the polar biome or are an intersection of environmental systems with entities that possess some polar quality. Furthermore, Polar Mountain is defined as a mountain that is part of a polar environment.",3,True
:has_definition ""A mountain that is part of a temperate environment.""^^xsd:string .

,A temperate mountain is a type of mountain that is characterized as part of an environmental system intersecting with entities that possess the quality of being temperate. This type of mountain is defined as a mountain that is part of a temperate environment.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001456,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A mountain that is part of a tropical environment.""^^xsd:string .

,A tropical mountain is a type of mountain that is part of or intersects with an environmental system, specifically one that is characterized by or possesses qualities of the tropics. It is defined as a mountain that is part of a tropical environment.",3,True

:has_definition ""A montane forest ecosystem which 1) is evergreen, 2) present on mountains where there is frequent cloud and mist cover, 3) which has a large proportion of ferns and mosses in its plant communities, growing on all tree trunks and branches present in the ecosystem, and 3) harvests aerosolised water and adds it to the terrestrial water supply.""

,A cloud forest is a type of montane forest characterized as an evergreen ecosystem present on mountains where there is frequent cloud and mist cover. It is distinguished by a large proportion of ferns and mosses in its plant communities, which grow on all tree trunks and branches within the ecosystem. Additionally, this ecosystem is notable for harvesting aerosolized water, contributing to the terrestrial water supply. A cloud forest falls within an ecological community that exclusively comprises members of the Viridiplantae and includes plants that are evergreen. It also participates in environmental system processes involving clouds and mist. Furthermore, ""cloud forest"" is exactly synonymous with ""tropical montane cloud forest.""",5,True
:has_definition ""A visible mass of water droplets or ice crystals suspended in the air at or near a planetary surface, formed when humid air cools rapidly."" .

,Mist is a type of aerosolized liquids and also a type of atmospheric aerosol. It is described as a visible mass of water droplets or ice crystals suspended in the air at or near a planetary surface, formed when humid air cools rapidly. Additionally, mist is characterized as something that at least has a part of something that is a union of water-based cloud droplet and water ice crystal. Furthermore, mist is identified as something that is at least located in some atmosphere, is an output of some condensation process, and is composed primarily of liquid water.",7,True
:has_definition ""A mountain which has a maximum elevation greater than 2500 metres above sea level."" .

,A high elevation mountain is a type of mountain that is defined as a mountain which has a maximum elevation greater than 2500 metres above sea level.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001460,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A mountain which has a maximum elevation between 300 and 2499 metres above sea level and slopes greater than or equal to two degrees of inclination."" .

,A mid-elevation mountain is a type of mountain characterized by having a maximum elevation between 300 and 2499 meters above sea level and slopes with an inclination of two degrees or greater.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001461,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation greater than 4500 metres above sea level."" .

,UNEP WCMC class 1 mountain is a type of high-elevation mountain which is defined as a high-elevation mountain with a maximum elevation greater than 4500 metres above sea level.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001462,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 3500 and 4500 metres above sea level."" .
,A UNEP WCMC class 2 mountain is a type of high elevation mountain, which is defined as a high-elevation mountain with a maximum elevation between 3500 and 4500 meters above sea level.",2,True
:has_definition ""A high-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 2500 and 3500 metres above sea level."" .
,The UNEP WCMC class 3 mountain is a type of high elevation mountain, defined as a high-elevation mountain with a maximum elevation ranging between 2500 and 3500 metres above sea level.",2,True
:has_definition ""A mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 1500 and 2499 metres above sea level and a slope greater than or equal to two degrees."" .

,UNEP WCMC Class 4 Mountain is a type of mid-elevation mountain which is defined as a mid-elevation mountain that has a maximum elevation between 1500 and 2499 metres above sea level and a slope greater than or equal to two degrees.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001465,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:has_definition ""A mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 1000 and 1499 metres above sea level and either 1) a slope greater than or equal to five degrees or 2) a local elevation range, within a 7 kilometre radius, of greater than 300 metres above sea level."" .

,UNEP WCMC class 5 mountain is categorized as a type of mid-elevation mountain, defined by having a maximum elevation between 1000 and 1499 meters above sea level. Additionally, it must meet one of the following conditions: a slope greater than or equal to five degrees or a local elevation range, within a 7-kilometer radius, of more than 300 meters above sea level.",2,True

:has_definition ""A mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 300 and 999 metres above sea level and a local elevation range, within a 7 kilometre radius, of greater than 300 metres above sea level."" .

,The UNEP WCMC class 6 mountain is a type of mid-elevation mountain. It is defined as a mid-elevation mountain which has a maximum elevation between 300 and 999 meters above sea level and possesses a local elevation range, within a 7-kilometer radius, of greater than 300 meters above sea level.",2,True
:has_definition ""An elevated inner basin or plateau surrounded by mountains, but not - itself - a mountain."" .

,The UNEP WCMC class 7 mountain is a type of elevated and surface landform. It is characterized by being a type that includes parts which are unions of plateau and depressed landforms, as well as high elevation and mid elevation mountains. Additionally, it is defined as an elevated inner basin or plateau surrounded by mountains, but it is not itself considered a mountain.",5,True
:has_definition ""An ecosystem which overlaps those areas of the foreshore and seabed that are exposed to the air at low tide and submerged at high tide.""^^xsd:string

,The intertidal ecosystem, a type of coastal wetland ecosystem, is characterized as a part of the shore that is, at least partially, exposed. It is defined as an ecosystem overlapping areas of the foreshore and seabed that are exposed to the air at low tide and submerged at high tide. Furthermore, ""coastal zone"" is considered a broad synonym, while ""IntertidalZone"" and ""littoral zone"" are related synonyms for the intertidal ecosystem.",6,True
:has_definition ""A system of constructed and manufactured products which are used by humans to produce data, information, or knowledge about material, immaterial, or processual entities."" .

,An observing system is categorized as a type of system that is, at a minimum, partly comprised of human construction and manufactured products. It is defined as a system of constructed and manufactured products which are utilized by humans to generate data, information, or knowledge about material, immaterial, or processual entities.",4,True
:has_definition ""An observing system which generates long-term data about one or more entities of interest, typically using standardised methodology."" .

,An observatory system is a type of observing system which has the definition of an observing system that generates long-term data about one or more entities of interest, typically using standardized methodology.",2,True

,atmospheric observatory system is a type of observatory system.,1,False
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001472,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

,marine observatory system is a type of observatory system.,1,False
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001473,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

,terrestrial observatory system is a type of observatory system.,1,False
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001474,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

,astronomical observatory system is a type of observatory system.,1,False
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001475,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:has_definition ""An observatory system which includes components used to generate (meta)genomic, (meta)transcriptomic, (meta)proteomic, metabolomic, and other omic data, information, and knowledge."" .

,The omics observatory system is a type of observatory system with a definition as follows: It is an observatory system which includes components used to generate (meta)genomic, (meta)transcriptomic, (meta)proteomic, metabolomic, and other omic data, information, and knowledge.",2,True
:has_definition ""A liquid astronomical body part which is continuous and is delimited by physical discontinuities or non-liquid boundaries.""@en .
,A body of liquid is a type of liquid astronomical body part, defined as a continuous liquid astronomical body part that is delimited by physical discontinuities or non-liquid boundaries.",2,True
:has_definition ""A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of a continuous volume of liquid material, shaped by one or more environmental processes."" .

,A liquid astronomical body part is defined as a part of an astronomical body that is primarily composed of a continuous volume of liquid material, shaped by one or more environmental processes. It is classified as a type of fluid astronomical body part, a type of compound astronomical body part, and a type of entity that is at least primarily composed of some liquid environmental material. Additionally, a liquid astronomical body part is the same as an entity that is the intersection of a fluid astronomical body part and an entity that is at least primarily composed of some liquid environmental material.",5,True
:has_definition ""A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of a continuous volume of gaseous material, shaped by one or more environmental processes."" .

,A gaseous astronomical body part is defined as a part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of a continuous volume of gaseous material, shaped by one or more environmental processes. It is considered the same as something that intersects with both a fluid astronomical body part and something that is at least composed primarily of some gaseous environmental material. Furthermore, a gaseous astronomical body part is categorized as a type of fluid astronomical body part, a type of compound astronomical body part, and also a type of something that is at least composed primarily of some gaseous environmental material.",5,True
:has_definition ""A part of an astronomical body which is primarily composed of a continuous volume of liquid or gaseous material, shaped by one or more environmental processes."" .

,A fluid astronomical body part is defined as a part of an astronomical body primarily composed of a continuous volume of liquid or gaseous material, shaped by one or more environmental processes. It is identical to an intersection of an astronomical body part and something that is at least composed primarily of either gaseous or liquid environmental material. Furthermore, a fluid astronomical body part is categorized as a type of astronomical body part and also as a type of entity that is primarily composed of a union of gaseous and liquid environmental materials.",4,True
:has_definition ""A building which is primarily used for the long-term habitation of humans."" .

,A domestic building is defined as a building primarily used for the long-term habitation of humans. It is identified as a type of building and also falls under the category of structures that, at a minimum, engage in the use of an environment for residential activity. Additionally, a domestic building is equivalent to an entity that is both a building and actively participates in some form of usage of an environment for residential purposes.",4,True
:has_definition ""A prison facility which is owned and operated by a state.""

,A public prison is a type of prison facility defined as a prison facility owned and operated by a state. It has exact synonyms including correctional facility, public correctional center, public correctional centre, public correctional facility, public detention center, public detention centre, public gaol, public jail, public lock-up, public penitentiary, public remand center, and public remand centre. Moreover, it has related synonyms such as detention center, gaol, jail, penitentiary, and remand center.",19,True

:has_definition ""A tornado is an aeroform consisting of at least one rapidly rotating column of air that is in contact with both the surface of an astronomical body and pendant from within or beneath a cumulonimbus or cumulus cloud.""@en

,A tornado is a type of aeroform that is defined as an aeroform consisting of at least one rapidly rotating column of air in contact with both the surface of an astronomical body and pendant from within or beneath a cumulonimbus or cumulus cloud. It is a phenomenon that encompasses characteristics such as being a type of entity that is part of or adjacent to something involving a union of cumulus and cumulonimbus clouds, atmospheric layers, and is also adjacent to other similar entities involving cumulus and cumulonimbus clouds. Additionally, a tornado possesses qualities that make it columnar in shape, is primarily composed of air, and is adjacent to a planetary surface. In terms of terminology, ""tornado"" has an exact synonym ""twister"" and related synonyms ""cyclone"" and ""whirlwind"".",9,True
:has_definition ""A surface layer where the solid or liquid material of an astronomical body comes into contact with an atmosphere or outer space.""

,The surface of an astronomical body is characterized in several ways. Firstly, it is synonymous with the land surface and is defined as a surface layer where the solid or liquid material of an astronomical body comes into contact with an atmosphere or outer space. It is equivalent to the intersection of a surface layer and an entity that is at least partially part of some astronomical body. Moreover, this surface is categorized under a few types: it is a type of surface layer itself and also a type of entity that is at least partially composed of astronomical bodies. Furthermore, it falls under the category of entities that are either adjacent to an atmosphere or outer space, or both. Additionally, it is considered a type of entity that is primarily composed of a union of solid and liquid environmental materials.",7,True

:has_definition ""A fire whirl is a whirlwind induced by the contraction and rotation of intense, rising heat and turbulent, eddying air masses resulting from a large fire and made up of a core of burning matter surrounded by a rotating pocket of air.""@en

,A fire whirl, also known as a fire devil or fire swirl, with related synonyms including fire tornado, fire twister, and firenado, is a type of aeroform. This phenomenon is characterized by its columnar quality and is formed as a result of a fire. It is defined as a whirlwind induced by the contraction and rotation of intense, rising heat and turbulent, eddying air masses resulting from a large fire, composed of a core of burning matter surrounded by a rotating pocket of air. Furthermore, a fire whirl is a specific type of entity that at least has a part that is an intersection of environmental material and a substance that has increased combustibility, highlighting its intense and dangerous nature.",10,True
:has_definition ""A tornado which comprises two or more columns of spinning air rotating about their own axis and at the same time around a common center.""@en .

,A multiple vortex tornado is a type of tornado that is defined as a tornado which comprises two or more columns of spinning air rotating about their own axis and at the same time around a common center.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001486,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:has_definition ""A tornado which a) is not associated with a mesocyclone and is thus relatively weak and short-lived, b) is centred on a small, smooth condensation funnel which often does not reach the planetary surface, and c) forms a distinctively laminar cloud of dust when it makes contact with the land.""@en
,A landspout is a type of tornado characterized by several distinct features: it is not associated with a mesocyclone, making it relatively weak and short-lived
column2: it is centered on a small, smooth condensation funnel which often does not reach the planetary surface
column3: and when it makes contact with the land, it forms a distinctively laminar cloud of dust. Moreover, a landspout is also exactly synonymous with several other terms: dust-tube tornado, fair weather waterspout on land, and land spout.",5,True

column1: :has_definition ""A tornado which connects a cumulus or cumulonimbus cloud to a body of water, often transporting water from that water body along the spiraling winds constituting  its vortex.""@en

,A waterspout is a type of tornado, which is defined as a tornado that connects a cumulus or cumulonimbus cloud to a body of water. It often transports water from that water body along the spiraling winds constituting its vortex. Moreover, a waterspout is also a type of phenomenon that occurs at the intersection of a surface that is at least adjacent to a water surface and a part of some water body, and is also adjacent to either a cumulus cloud or a cumulonimbus cloud. Additionally, waterspout has an exact synonym, ""water spout.""",4,True
:has_definition ""A vehicle which is able to travel through air in an atmosphere."" .

,An aircraft is a type of vehicle defined as a vehicle capable of traveling through the air in an atmosphere.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001489,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A slope of land descending laterally from a hill, mountain or main crest of a ridge.""@en

,A spur is a type of slope and is defined as a slope of land descending laterally from a hill, mountain, or main crest of a ridge. It is also a type of feature that is at least partly composed of rock and can be part of a feature that includes mountains, hills, and ridges. Additionally, ""spurs"" is a related synonym in physiographic terms.",5,True
:has_definition ""A mass of environmental material which has been formed as the result of its transport into an existing mass of another material."" .

,An intrusion is a type of solid astronomical body part and is also a type of something that at least has the quality of some protruding into. Moreover, an intrusion is defined as a mass of environmental material which has been formed as the result of its transport into an existing mass of another material.",3,True
:has_definition ""An elevation which is flattened across its highest surface.""@en .

,Flattened elevation is characterized by being the same as an intersection of an elevated landform and something that possesses, at the very least, a quality of being somewhat flattened. It is not only a type of elevated landform but also falls under the category of entities that have a quality of being somewhat flattened. Furthermore, flattened elevation is defined as an elevation that is flattened across its highest surface.",4,True
:has_definition ""A remote sensing process during which image data about an astronomical body or object is generated by sensors mounted on a satellite."" .

,Satellite imaging is a planned process that involves generating image data about astronomical bodies or objects through a remote sensing process. This process is conducted by sensors mounted on a satellite and results in the production of images. It is characterized by its engagement with entities that are either astronomical bodies or astronomical objects.,4,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001493,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A remote sensing process during which image data about a planet is generated by sensors mounted on a satellite."" .

,Satellite imaging of a planet is a type of satellite imaging, as well as a type of environmental system process. It is also recognized as a type of process that involves at least one planet as a participant. Satellite imaging of a planet is defined as a remote sensing process during which image data about a planet is generated by sensors mounted on a satellite.",4,True

,moonmoon is a type of astronomical body.,1,False
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001495,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""Dioxygen which is the solute in a solution with ocean water as its solvent.""

,Dioxygen dissolved in marine water is a type of dioxygen, which is at least part of some sea water and has the quality of being dissolved. It is defined as dioxygen which is the solute in a solution with ocean water as its solvent. Furthermore, it is broadly synonymous with dissolved oxygen and oceanic oxygen, and is also relatedly synonymous with oxygen.",7,True
:has_definition ""A macronutrient role which inheres in nitrate, nitrogen dioxide, ammonium, silicon, or phosphate dissolved in ocean water."" .

,Inorganic macronutrients dissolved in ocean water represent a specific category of macronutrients. These macronutrients are characterized by being a part of a group that includes nitrate, phosphate, silicon atoms, ammonium, and nitrogen oxide, all of which are, at least in part, constituents of sea water and share the quality of being dissolved. Furthermore, the role of an inorganic macronutrient dissolved in ocean water is defined by its association with substances such as nitrate, nitrogen dioxide, ammonium, silicon, or phosphate, all of which are found dissolved in ocean water.",3,True

:has_definition ""A system which is composed of carbon-based chemical entities dissolved in or otherwise part of an ocean or sea and the atmosphere adjacent to it, undergoing constant exchange through biogeochemical cycling.""

,The carbonate system of ocean water is a system that encompasses various aspects. It is recognized as a type of system that inherently includes at least a part of the atmosphere. Additionally, it is defined as a system that comprises parts which intersect between sea water and entities that are both chemical in nature and include carbon atoms as a part of their composition. This system actively participates in processes such as ocean acidification and carbon cycling, highlighting its dynamic role in the marine environment. A precise definition describes it as a system consisting of carbon-based chemical entities that are dissolved in or are part of the ocean or sea and the adjacent atmosphere, engaging in continuous exchange through biogeochemical cycling. Furthermore, the carbonate system of ocean water is also referred to by exact synonyms such as the carbonate system of the sea and the marine carbonate system, underscoring its significance in marine science.",8,True
:has_definition ""A process by which landforms are formed from the thawing of ice-rich permafrost or the melting of massive ground ice.""

,The thermokarst formation process is equivalent to an intersection of environmental system processes and activities that ultimately result in the formation of thermokarst. This process is categorized as a type of hydrological and biological process. Additionally, it encompasses processes that involve material transport and the thawing of ice-bearing permafrost, both of which are crucial components. The thermokarst formation process also leads to the creation of thermokarst, including the formation of thermokarst lakes and depressions. It is defined as a process through which landforms are created from the thawing of ice-rich permafrost or the melting of massive ground ice. Furthermore, the term ""thermokarst"" is an exact synonym for the thermokarst formation process.",9,True
:has_definition ""An active ecosystem management process which targets an agricultural ecosystem.""

,The active agri ecosystem management process is a specific kind of active ecosystem management process that is intricately linked to agricultural activities. It is characterized by its incorporation of or association with agricultural processes and involves participation from entities that are part of or related to cropland, village, and rangeland biomes. This process is defined as an active ecosystem management approach focusing on agricultural ecosystems. Furthermore, it is synonymously known as agri-ecosystem management and has related synonyms including Agrarumweltmaßnahme, agri-environmental management, and agricultural environment management.",8,True
:has_definition ""A pollution process during which artificial light with wavelengths in the visible spectrum is released into the environment.""

,Anthropogenic light pollution is a type of anthropogenic environmental process and a type of environmental pollution, which involves a pollution process during which artificial light with wavelengths in the visible spectrum is released into the environment. This phenomenon is characterized by being a type of entity that at least has part some visible spectrum radiation from a manufactured product. Furthermore, anthropogenic light pollution is exactly synonymous with ""Lichtverschmutzung.""",5,True
:has_definition ""An electromagnetic radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted from a manufactured product.""

,Radiation from a manufactured product is identified as a type of electromagnetic radiation and also as a type that results from at least one process that has some manufactured product as its causal agent. This specific radiation is equivalent to the intersection of electromagnetic radiation and a process with a manufactured product playing a pivotal role in its cause. It is defined as an electromagnetic radiation process during which electromagnetic waves or their quanta are emitted from a manufactured product. Furthermore, this type of radiation is broadly synonymous with anthropogenic radiation and exactly synonymous with artificial radiation.",6,True
:has_definition ""Radiation from a manufactured product during which light between the wavelenghts of 380 nm and 760 nm is emitted.""

,Visible spectrum radiation from a manufactured product is a type of radiation that emanates from manufactured products, specifically emitting light between the wavelengths of 380 nm and 760 nm. Additionally, this form of radiation is precisely synonymous with optical radiation from a manufactured product.",3,True
:has_definition ""A solid surface layer which is that part of a glacier in contact with a planetary atmosphere, water body, or solid material partially surrounding that glacier.""

,The glacial surface layer, which is also precisely known as the glacier surface, is defined as a solid surface layer. This layer constitutes the part of a glacier that comes in contact with a planetary atmosphere, a water body, or solid material partially surrounding that glacier. Additionally, it is identified as a type of solid surface layer and a component that constitutes at least part of some glacier.",4,True
:has_definition ""A velocity quality which inheres in the surface layer of a glacier.""

,Glacial surface layer velocity is a type of velocity that inherently possesses defining characteristics of some glacial surface layer. It is defined as a velocity quality which inheres in the surface layer of a glacier. Furthermore, glacial surface layer velocity is exactly synonymous with glacier surface layer velocity and glacier surface velocity.",5,True

:has_definition ""A tundra biome which exists at high altitudes and where vegetation - dominated by a few species of dwarf shrubs, a few grasses, sedges, lichens, and mosses - is stunted due to low temperatures and high winds.""^^xsd:string

,The alpine tundra biome is a specific type of both tundra and alpine biomes. It is defined as a tundra biome that is situated at high altitudes, characterized by vegetation that is dominated by a limited variety of dwarf shrubs, a few grasses, sedges, lichens, and mosses. This vegetation is stunted due to the low temperatures and high winds typical of such environments. The alpine tundra biome is also precisely known as mountain tundra.",4,True
:has_definition ""An ice mass which has calved off an larger mass of ice.""

,An ice calf is a type of ice mass and also a type of something that is at least the output of some ice calving process. It is defined as an ice mass which has calved off a larger mass of ice. Additionally, ""calved ice"" is an exact synonym for ice calf.",4,True
:has_definition ""An ice calf which is suspended in a water mass, being partially exposed to an atmosphere."" .
,A floating ice calf is a type of ice calf and also a type of floating ice mass. It is defined as an ice calf which is suspended in a water mass, being partially exposed to an atmosphere.",3,True
:has_definition ""An ice calf which is frozen to the bed of an ocean or other water body."" .

,An anchored ice calf is a type of caro 0000003 and is also a type of ice calf. It is defined as an ice calf that is frozen to the bed of an ocean or another water body. This type of ice calf is characterized by being at least attached to some submerged bed and is composed primarily of some anchor ice.,5,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001509,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""An ice calf which rests on land."" .
,A terrestrial ice calf is a type of ice calf that is defined as an ice calf which rests on land. Additionally, it is a type of entity that is at least adjacent to some planetary landmass.",3,True
:has_definition ""A material transformation process during which a material's viscosity increase either through a reduction in temperature, through chemical reactions, or other physical effects.""

,The material congelation process is identified as a specific category of material transformation process. It is characterized as a process that results in an output intersecting with environmental material, which notably possesses an increased viscosity. Furthermore, the material congelation process is defined as a material transformation process during which a material's viscosity increases, either through a reduction in temperature, through chemical reactions, or other physical effects. Additionally, this process is precisely synonymous with both ""congelation"" and ""congelation process.""",5,True

,Freshwater ice is a type of water ice and something that is at least composed primarily of some fresh water.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001512,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

:has_definition ""Sea ice which 1) has formed on the submerged surface (i.e. the base) of an existing mass of sea ice and 2) is composed of columnar crystals due to the downward growth of the crystals into the water.""

,Congelation sea ice is a type of sea ice notable for forming on the submerged surface, or base, of an existing mass of sea ice. It is characterized by its composition of columnar crystals, which grow downward into the water. This formation process makes it a subset of sea ice that is at least partially surrounded by a mixture of sea water and sea ice. Additionally, congelation sea ice is commonly referred to by its synonym, ""black ice.""",5,True
:has_definition ""Water ice which has formed in a mass of permafrost."" .

,Permafrost congelation ice is a type of water ice and is also classified as a part of some permafrost. It is defined as water ice that has formed in a mass of permafrost.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001514,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""Freshwater ice which forms downward from the surface of a freshwater water body and is transparent due to a reduced number of air bubbles trapped in its mass.""

,Congelation ice in a fresh water body is a type of freshwater congelation ice, which is defined as freshwater ice that forms downward from the surface of a freshwater water body and is transparent due to a reduced number of air bubbles trapped in its mass. Additionally, congelation ice in a fresh water body is exactly synonymous with black ice.",3,True
:has_definition ""Freshwater ice which forms on a solid substrate through the freezing of freshwater."" .
,Freshwater congelation ice is a type of freshwater ice, defined as freshwater ice that forms on a solid substrate through the freezing of freshwater.",2,True
:has_definition ""Freshwater congelation ice which has formed on a solid substrate in an ice cave."" .

,Ice cave congelation ice is a type of freshwater congelation ice, which is found in locations that are the union of glacier caves and ice caves. It is defined as freshwater congelation ice that has formed on a solid substrate in an ice cave.",3,True
:has_definition ""A floating mass of ice which is 1) unattached to land or land-fast ice and 2) moved by the action of winds or currents."" .

,A drift ice mass is a type of floating ice mass, defined as a floating mass of ice that is 1) unattached to land or land-fast ice and 2) moved by the action of winds or currents. Additionally, drift ice mass is broadly synonymous with drift ice.",3,True
:has_definition ""A drift ice mass which is composed primarily of sea ice."" .

,A drifting sea ice mass is a type of drift ice mass and also a type of sea ice mass. It is defined as a drift ice mass primarily composed of sea ice. Additionally, it has a broad synonym: drift ice.",4,True
:has_definition ""An area in which masses of drift ice aggregate such that they cover a minimum of 7/10ths-8/10ths of the surface the water body they are floating in."" .

,The area of pack ice is categorized as a type of environmental zone, which also qualifies as a type that overlaps with water bodies to some extent. Additionally, it is defined as a type that overlaps with entities that are at the intersection of being both an object aggregate and primarily composed of drift ice mass, further characterized by an increased concentration. The area of pack ice is specifically defined as an area where masses of drift ice come together to cover a minimum of 70% to 80% of the surface of the water body they float in.",4,True
:has_definition ""An environmental zone that overlaps that part of a water body covered or partially covered by sea ice.""

,The area of sea ice is a type of environmental zone that at least overlaps some water body and also overlaps some sea ice. It is defined as an environmental zone that overlaps that part of a water body covered or partially covered by sea ice. Additionally, the area of sea ice has an exact synonym: area with sea ice.",5,True
:has_definition ""An area in which masses of drift ice aggregate such that they cover less than 7/10ths of the surface the water body they are floating in."" .

,The area of drift ice is defined as an environmental zone that overlaps with a water body to some extent. It is also characterized by overlapping with an intersection of objects that aggregate and are primarily composed of drift ice masses. Specifically, an area of drift ice is defined as an area where masses of drift ice come together such that they cover less than 7/10ths of the surface of the water body they are floating in.",4,True

:has_definition ""A mass of sea ice which 1) is less than 2 meters in thickness and 2) forms along the coast, where it is attached to the shore, to an ice wall, to an ice front, or between shoals or grounded icebergs."" .

,Fast ice is a type of caro 0000003 and also a type of sea ice mass. Furthermore, it is described as a type of entity that is at least attached to something which is a union of the shore and an intersection of an object and something that is at least attached to a marine bed. Additionally, fast ice is defined as a mass of sea ice which is less than 2 meters in thickness and forms along the coast, where it is attached to the shore, to an ice wall, to an ice front, or between shoals or grounded icebergs.",4,True
:has_definition ""Small, needle-like (spicules), plate-like, or discoid crystals derived from nearly pure fresh water, suspended in a water body.""

,Frazil is a type of new ice, which is at least partially surrounded by some liquid water, has a decreased size, and derives from some fresh water. It is defined as small, needle-like (spicules), plate-like, or discoid crystals derived from nearly pure fresh water, suspended in a water body. Frazil also has exact synonyms frazil crystals and needle ice.",7,True
:has_definition ""Land which is below the freezing point of water.""

,Frozen land is equal to an intersection of land and anything that possesses at least some quality of being frozen. It is a type of land and also a type of entity that has at least some quality of being frozen. Furthermore, frozen land is a type of entity that is primarily composed of materials that are either rock or soil. Frozen land is defined as land which is below the freezing point of water, and it has an exact synonym, ""frozen ground.""",6,True
:has_definition ""Frozen soil which is firmly cemented by water ice, is subject to brittle failure, and exhibits practically no consolidation under load."" .

,Hard frozen soil is a type of solid environmental material and a type of frozen soil. It is also characterized as a type of material that at least partially contains water ice and possesses the quality of being hard. Additionally, hard frozen soil is defined as frozen soil which is firmly cemented by water ice, is subject to brittle failure, and exhibits practically no consolidation under load.",5,True
:has_definition ""Soil which is below the freezing point of water."" .

,Frozen soil is the same as something that intersects with soil and something that has at least some quality of being frozen. It is a type of soil and also a type of something that is at least partly some frozen land. Furthermore, frozen soil is a type of something that has at least some quality of being frozen. Frozen soil is defined as soil which is below the freezing point of water.",5,True
:has_definition ""Frozen soil which is cemented by water ice but has viscous properties due to its high, unfrozen water content and therefore will compress and deform under load."" .

,Plastic frozen soil is a type of frozen soil and also a type of material that contains some amount of liquid water. It is defined as frozen soil which is cemented by water ice but has viscous properties due to its high, unfrozen water content, and therefore, it will compress and deform under load.",3,True
:has_definition ""Frozen soil which has very low total water content and is not cemented by ice
column2: its compressibility is the same as that of unfrozen soils having the same composition, total water content and density.""

column1: ,Friable frozen soil is a type of solid environmental and frozen soil, which at least partially comprises water ice and possesses the quality of being hard. It is defined as frozen soil with a very low total water content, not cemented by ice, and its compressibility is identical to that of unfrozen soils with the same composition, total water content, and density. Furthermore, friable frozen soil is exactly synonymous with dry-frozen soil.",6,True
:has_definition ""An ice mass which constitutes that part of a glacier which has the lowest elevation.""

,A glacier snout is a type of land ice mass, which constitutes that part of a glacier which has the lowest elevation, making it a specific segment of a glacier with decreased elevation. It is also known as glacier terminus or glacier toe, indicating its position as the forefront or the lowest part of a glacier.",6,True

:has_definition ""An ice mass which has been drilled from an accumulation of snow and ice that has built up over many years and that has recrystallized and has trapped air bubbles from previous time periods."" .

,A water ice core is a type of ice mass, which is also broadly synonymous with both an ice core and an ice sample. It is characterized by being a part of entities that intersect with air and are at least surrounded by water ice. Additionally, a water ice core is derived from entities that are an intersection of ice mass and those that are at least surrounded by an ice mass. The definition of a water ice core is an ice mass that has been drilled from an accumulation of snow and ice, which has built up over many years. This accumulation has recrystallized and trapped air bubbles from previous time periods.",6,True
:has_definition ""An ice field which is primarily composoed of sea ice floes greater than 10 kilometers across."" .

,A sea ice field is a type of ice field that is primarily composed of sea ice. It is a type of entity that has at least one ice floe member, with these ice floes being greater than 10 kilometers across. This definition characterizes a sea ice field as an ice field primarily composed of such large sea ice floes. Additionally, a sea ice field is broadly synonymous with a floating ice field.",5,True
:has_definition ""An ice field which is constituted by a continuous accumulation of snow and glacier ice that completely fills a mountain basin or covers a low-relief mountain plateau."" .

,A glacier ice field is a type of ice field that is characterized by being at least partially surrounded by structures that are part of a union between structural basins and mountains, as well as being adjacent to areas where plateaus and mountains intersect. Furthermore, a glacier ice field is comprised primarily of materials that consist of a union between glacial ice and an intersection of snow with parts of glaciers. The definition of a glacier ice field is an ice field constituted by a continuous accumulation of snow and glacier ice that either completely fills a mountain basin or covers a low-relief mountain plateau.",4,True
:has_definition ""An advective transport process during which a mass of ice is transported from one location to another."" .

,Mass ice flow is a type of advective transport process and something that involves at least some ice mass as a participant. It is defined as an advective transport process during which a mass of ice is transported from one location to another.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001534,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""An iceberg which 1) has a flat upper surface, 2) is derived from an ice shelf, ice tongue, or floating tidewater glacier via detachment.""^^xsd:string

,A tabular iceberg is a type of marine iceberg characterized by a flat upper surface. It belongs to a category of icebergs that have at least a part of a surface layer and possess a flattened quality. Additionally, a tabular iceberg originates from either an ice shelf, an ice tongue, or through the detachment of a floating tidewater glacier. It is precisely defined as an iceberg with a flat upper surface, which is derived from an ice shelf, ice tongue, or floating tidewater glacier via detachment. Tabular icebergs are also known by their exact synonyms: barrier iceberg, table iceberg, and tabular berg.",7,True

:has_definition ""An ice mass which is composed of a large amount of sea ice in the form of a hummock or a group of such hummocks, frozen together and separated from any surrounding ice by sea water.""^^xsd:string .

,Floeberg is a type of sea ice mass and is also a type of entity that includes, at least in part, some sea ice hummocks. It is defined as an ice mass which consists largely of sea ice in the form of a hummock or a group of such hummocks, these being frozen together and isolated from any surrounding ice by sea water.",3,True
:has_definition ""An ice mass which is composed primarily of sea ice."" .

,Sea ice mass is a type of ice mass that is at least composed primarily of sea ice. It shares the same characteristics as something that is an intersection of ice mass and something that is at least composed primarily of sea ice. Moreover, sea ice mass is defined as an ice mass which is composed primarily of sea ice.",4,True
:has_definition ""An elevation which is formed by pressure at the point of contact between ice floes, resulting in a conglomeration of broken ice.""^^xsd:string .

,A sea ice hummock is a type of elevated, surface, and cryoform landform, which is at least composed primarily of sea ice. It is defined as an elevation formed by pressure at the point of contact between ice floes, resulting in a conglomeration of broken ice.",5,True
:has_definition ""A hummock which is primarily composed of soil that has been pushed up by frost action.""^^xsd:string .

,A frost-formed hummock is a type of hummock and also a type of frost heave. This particular kind of hummock is characterized by being composed primarily of a combination of permafrost and soil. It is defined as a hummock that is primarily made up of soil which has been elevated due to the action of frost. Additionally, ""hummock"" is considered a broad synonym for a frost-formed hummock.",5,True
:has_definition ""A valley glacier which has one or more tributary glaciers as parts.""^^xsd:string .

,A branched valley glacier is a type of valley glacier that is characterized by having one or more tributary glaciers as parts and possessing the quality of being branched. It is defined as a valley glacier that has one or more tributary glaciers as parts.,4,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001540,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A valley glacier which does not have any tributary glaciers flowing into it.""^^xsd:string .

,A simple valley glacier is a specific type of valley glacier characterized by not having any tributary glaciers flowing into it.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001541,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A glacier which flows into a larger glacier.""^^xsd:string .

,A tributary glacier is a type of glacier that is at least partially surrounded by and adjacent to some valley. It is defined as a glacier which flows into a larger glacier.,4,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001542,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A surface layer which is composed primarily of ice."" .

,The ice surface layer is a type of solid surface layer and is something that is at least composed primarily of ice. It is defined as a surface layer which is composed primarily of ice.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001543,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""An ice surface layer which is primarily composed of water ice."" .

,The water ice surface layer is a type of water ice layer, a type of ice surface layer, and also a type of surface of an astronomical body. It is defined as an ice surface layer which is primarily composed of water ice.",4,True
:has_definition ""An two-dimensional continuant fiat boundary which overlaps the surface layer of a mass of ice."" .

,A two-dimensional fiat ice surface is a type of two-dimensional continuant fiat boundary and is also categorized as something that overlaps at least some ice surface layer. Furthermore, it is defined as a two-dimensional continuant fiat boundary which overlaps the surface layer of a mass of ice.",3,True
:has_definition ""A two-dimensional fiat ice surface which is composed primarily of water ice."" .

,A two-dimensional fiat water ice surface is a type of two-dimensional fiat ice surface. It is also a type of entity that at least overlaps some water ice surface layer. Furthermore, it is defined as a two-dimensional fiat ice surface that is composed primarily of water ice.",3,True
:has_definition ""An ice mass which has broken away from a larger ice mass on land, such as a glacier or ice shelf, and may be either afloat or aground.""^^xsd:string .
,An iceberg is a type of land ice mass, defined as an ice mass that has broken away from a larger ice mass on land, such as a glacier or ice shelf, and may be either afloat or aground.",2,True
rdf:rest [ rdf:first [ owl:intersectionOf [ rdf:first [ a owl:Restriction
:has_definition ""An ice mass which has formed over land.""^^xsd:string .

,Land ice mass is a type of ice mass and also a type of entity that forms at the intersection of water freezing into water ice and occurrences that take place on a site which overlaps some planetary landmass. Additionally, a land ice mass is defined as an ice mass that has formed over land.",3,True
:has_definition ""A material congelation process during which a liquid turns into a solid when its temperature is lowered below its melting point."" .

,Freezing is a type of material congelation process defined as the process during which a liquid turns into a solid when its temperature is lowered below its melting point.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001549,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A freezing process during which liquid water is transformed into water ice."" .

,The freezing of water into water ice is defined as a freezing process during which liquid water is transformed into water ice. This process is the same as the intersection of something that involves freezing, as well as something that at least has input some liquid water and something that at least has output some water ice. Furthermore, the freezing of water into water ice is classified as a type of freezing, a type of hydrological process, a type of something that at least has input some liquid water, and a type of something that at least has output some water ice.",6,True
:has_definition ""An ice lead which occurs in a marine water body and is bounded by sea ice."" .

,A sea ice lead is a specific type of ice lead that is adjacent to at least two entities intersecting with something composed primarily of sea ice and an ice mass. It is defined as an ice lead occurring in a marine water body and is bounded by sea ice. Additionally, ""lead"" is considered a broad synonym for a sea ice lead.",4,True
:has_definition ""A surface layer of a water body which has been formed as the result of surface ice fracturing and moving apart."" .

,Ice lead is a type of surface layer of a water body and is something that is at least adjacent to some ice mass. It is defined as a surface layer of a water body which has been formed as the result of surface ice fracturing and moving apart. Additionally, ice lead has a broad synonym: lead.",4,True
:has_definition ""An ice lead between a mass of fast ice and a mass of pack ice."" .

,Flaw lead is a type of ice lead that is, at a minimum, adjacent to some fast ice and some pack ice mass. It is defined as an ice lead between a mass of fast ice and a mass of pack ice. Additionally, ""lead"" is considered a broad synonym for flaw lead.",5,True
:has_definition ""An ice lead which occurs between the shore and pack ice."" .

,Shore lead is a type of ice lead that is adjacent to both a shore and a pack ice mass. It is defined as an ice lead which occurs between the shore and pack ice. Additionally, shore lead is broadly synonymous with the term ""lead.""",5,True
:has_definition ""A water surface that is part of a water body."" .

,The surface layer of a water body is defined as a water surface that is part of a water body. It is simultaneously identified as a type of water surface, a type of surface of an astronomical body, and a type of entity that constitutes at least part of some water body. Furthermore, this layer is equivalent to an entity that exists at the intersection of a water surface and an entity that constitutes at least part of a water body.",5,True
:has_definition ""An ice lead within which new, nilas, and young ice has formed."" .

,Frozen lead is a type of ice lead and also broadly synonymous with lead. It is characterized as a type of entity that comprises at least a part of something which is a combination of new ice, nilas, and young ice. Additionally, a frozen lead is defined as an ice lead within which new, nilas, and young ice has formed.",4,True
:has_definition ""A drift ice mass which has an ice concentration above or equal to 7/10: which covers 70% or more of a given area of a water body.""

,Pack ice mass, a type of drift ice mass, is defined as a drift ice mass that has an ice concentration above or equal to 7/10, covering 70% or more of a given area of a water body. Additionally, pack ice mass is also known by its related synonym, drift ice.",3,True
:has_definition ""Ice which has formed as the result of freezing of water which was part of a water body."" .

,Water body derived ice is a type of water ice that forms as a result of the freezing of water, which is an output of a process that occurs in some water bodies. It is defined as ice that has formed as the result of the freezing of water which was part of a water body.",3,True

:has_definition ""An environmental zone which overlaps that part of an ocean or sea within which 1) sea ice is present only part of the year, 2) extends from the permanent ice zone to the boundary where winter sea ice extent is at a maximum, and 3) primarily overlaps first-year ice when seasonal ice is present."" .

,The area of seasonal sea ice is identified as a type of environmental zone. It is defined as an environmental zone that overlaps with that part of an ocean or sea where sea ice is present only part of the year. This area extends from the permanent ice zone to the boundary where winter sea ice extent reaches its maximum. Moreover, it primarily overlaps first-year ice when seasonal ice is present.",2,True
:has_definition ""A layer which is composed of ground that 1) remains unfrozen due to increased solute concentration and 2) is present within a mass of permafrost."" .

,Cryopeg is a type of cryospheric layer and also a type of something that is at least part of some permafrost. It is defined as a layer which is composed of ground that remains unfrozen due to increased solute concentration and is present within a mass of permafrost.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001560,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

:has_definition ""An environmental material which is primarily composed of a dispersed phase of insoluable particles, approximately between 1 nanometer and 1 micrometer in maximum dimension, distributed throughout a material acting as a medium of suspension."" .

,A colloidal suspension is a type of environmental material that encompasses materials which are at least partially composed of entities that are both environmental materials and possess qualities of being dispersed and granular. It is defined as an environmental material primarily made up of a dispersed phase of insoluble particles, with sizes ranging approximately between 1 nanometer and 1 micrometer, that are distributed throughout a substance acting as a medium of suspension. Furthermore, colloidal suspension is broadly synonymous with colloid.",4,True

:has_definition ""An environmental material which is solid, jelly-like, and exhibits no flow when in steady state material and which contains liquid dispersed in and held in place by cross-linked structures of a solid medium."" .

,Gel is identified as a type of solid environmental material that incorporates at least some portion of solid environmental material as well as some portion of liquid environmental material. Furthermore, a gel is defined as an environmental material that is solid, jelly-like, and exhibits no flow when in a steady-state, containing liquid dispersed in and held in place by cross-linked structures of a solid medium.",4,True
:has_definition ""A gel which is primarily composed of a network of polymer chains that are hydrophilic, sometimes found as a colloidal gel in which water is the dispersion medium."" .

,Hydrogel is a type of gel that is at least composed primarily of water. Additionally, hydrogel is defined as a gel which is primarily composed of a network of polymer chains that are hydrophilic, and it is sometimes found as a colloidal gel in which water is the dispersion medium.",3,True

:has_definition ""Particulate environmental material which 1) is primarily composed of a fine, granular material such as sand, silt, or clay suspended in and saturated by water and 2) readily liquefies when weight is applied, losing strength and permitting objects to sink until their weight and buoyancy offset the weight of the displaced quicksand.""@en .

,Quicksand is recognized as a type of particulate environmental material with several distinct qualities. It is inherently porous and unstructured, embodying a composition that intersects the characteristics of colloidal suspensions and hydrogels, primarily consisting of materials such as clay, silt, and sand. The definition of quicksand encapsulates it as a particulate environmental material that is primarily composed of a fine, granular material like sand, silt, or clay, which is suspended in and saturated by water. This material readily liquefies upon the application of weight, losing its strength which allows objects to sink until the weight of the object and the buoyancy balance out with the weight of the displaced quicksand.",5,True
:has_definition ""An aggregate of raindrops falling to a planetary surface during a precipitation process."" .

,Rain is classified as an object aggregate and is also considered as something that participates in some precipitation process. Furthermore, rain is characterized by having raindrops as members. It is defined as an aggregate of raindrops falling to a planetary surface during a precipitation process.",4,True
:has_definition ""Rain which is composed of water droplets falling to a planetary surface during a rainfall process."" .

,Water-based rain is a type of rain that at least participates in some water-based rainfall and has at least some water raindrop as a member. It is defined as rain which is composed of water droplets falling to a planetary surface during a rainfall process.,4,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001566,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""Sound which is lower in frequency than 20 Hertz, or cycles per second."" .

,Infrasound is a type of acoustic radiation defined as sound which is lower in frequency than 20 Hertz, or cycles per second. It is also broadly synonymous with inaudible sound and low-frequency sound.",4,True

:has_definition ""An environmental zone which 1) contains ecosystems, constructed features, or other entities deemed to be of natural, historical, cultural, or other significance and 2) has been afforded legal protections restricting one or more forms of use by a competent authority.""

,A protected area is a type of environmental zone, which is defined as an environmental zone that contains ecosystems, constructed features, or other entities deemed to be of natural, historical, cultural, or other significance and has been afforded legal protections restricting one or more forms of use by a competent authority. Furthermore, a protected area is related to the synonyms preserve and reserve.",4,True
:has_definition ""An elevation which is formed as an ice mass forms under soil, resulting in upwards deformation of the land surface.""

,Frost heave is defined as an elevation formed when an ice mass develops under the soil, causing the land surface to deform upwards. It is a type of elevated landform, surface landform, and also falls under the category of formations that result from the frost heaving process. Additionally, frost heave is exactly synonymous with frost heaving. Essentially, frost heave is the same as an intersection of landforms that are both surface features and are formed as a result of the frost heaving process.",6,True
:has_definition ""An ecoregion which is located on a landmass."" .

,A terrestrial ecoregion is a type of ecoregion and is defined as an ecoregion that is located on a landmass. It is also characterized as a type of region that is at least adjacent to some planetary landmass.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001581,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
:has_definition ""A surface layer which is part of an ocean or sea.""@en .

,The sea surface layer is identical to the intersection of the surface layer of a water body and at least part of the union of an ocean and a sea. It is classified as a type of marine layer and also as a type of surface layer of a water body. Furthermore, the sea surface layer is defined as a surface layer that is part of an ocean or sea.",4,True
:has_definition ""Land which is present within a forest biome."" .

,The forest floor is a type of land defined as land which is present within a forest biome.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001606,@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .

,The speed of a water current is a type of speed that is characteristic of some water currents.,2,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001607,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A hydroform which is maintained by a continuous, directed movement of water, generated by disequilibria in a water mass."" .
,Water current, a type of hydroform, is defined as a hydroform which is maintained by a continuous, directed movement of water, generated by disequilibria in a water mass.",2,True

:has_definition ""A fuel oil which 1) is derived from petroleum oil, 2) has a strong odor, 3) produces large quantities of soot relative to other fuel oils, 4) is less refined than fuel oils such as paraffin.""

,Kerosene oil, which is a type of fuel oil, is also known as kerosene or kerosine, with exact synonyms being kerosine oil and liquid kerosene. It is derived from petroleum and has specific characteristics including a strong odor, the production of large quantities of soot compared to other fuel oils, and being less refined than fuels such as paraffin.",7,True
:has_definition ""A layer which is part of a cryosphere."" .

,The cryospheric layer is a type of layer that is defined as a layer which is part of a cryosphere. It is equivalent to something that intersects with a layer and something that is at least part of some cryosphere. Additionally, the cryospheric layer is recognized as a type of something that is at least part of some cryosphere.",4,True
:has_definition ""A layer of environmental material which is subject to freeze-thaw cycles."" .

,The active layer in a cryosphere is a specific type of cryospheric layer, which is characterized by being primarily composed of environmental material that undergoes processes involving freezing and the combination of melting and thawing. This layer is defined as a layer of environmental material subject to freeze-thaw cycles. Additionally, the active layer in a cryosphere is broadly synonymous with the term ""active layer.""",4,True
:has_definition ""A warming process during which the thermal energy in a portion of environmental material is sufficient to melt water-based ice or snow."" .

,The thawing process is a type of material warming process and is defined as a warming process during which the thermal energy in a portion of environmental material is sufficient to melt water-based ice or snow. It is also broadly synonymous with thawing.,3,True
envo,http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01001612,@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
:has_definition ""A process during which the temperature of a portion of environmental material is increased, along with the kinetic energy of its constituent molecules."" .

,The material warming process, which is a type of material transformation process, is defined as a process during which the temperature of a portion of environmental material is increased, along with the kinetic energy of its constituent molecules.",2,True
:has_definition ""A thawing process during which permafrost is warmed beyond the melting point of water-based ice, snow, or other forms of solid water."" .

,The permafrost thawing process, a specific type of thawing process, is defined as a thawing process during which permafrost is warmed beyond the melting point of water-based ice, snow, or other forms of solid water.",2,True
:has_definition ""Permafrost which contains inclusions of water-based ice."" .

,Ice bearing permafrost is the same as something that intersects permafrost and something that at least has a part that is some water ice. Additionally, ice bearing permafrost is a type of permafrost and also a type of something that at least has part some water ice. Furthermore, ice bearing permafrost is defined as permafrost that contains inclusions of water-based ice.",4,True
:has_definition ""A process during which the temperature of a portion of environmental material is decreased, along with the kinetic energy of its constituent molecules."" .

,The material cooling process is a type of material transformation process and also falls under something that is at least part of some material congelation process. It is defined as a process during which the temperature of a portion of environmental material is decreased, along with the kinetic energy of its constituent molecules.",3,True
:has_definition ""Soil which is directly exposed to the atmosphere - with no intervening layer of plant life or other cover - and thus the effects of weathering and erosion."" .

,Bare soil is a type of soil that is directly exposed to the atmosphere, with no intervening layer of plant life or other cover, thus subject to the effects of weathering and erosion. It is also defined as being adjacent to some vegetation layer and at least adjacent to some troposphere. This categorization emphasizes its exposure and relationship to surrounding environmental elements.",4,True
:has_definition ""A material accumulation process during which the mass of snow on a surface increases."" .

,The snow accumulation process is a type of material accumulation process and also falls under the category of a biological process. It involves at least some surface layer and snow as participants. Additionally, this process results in the formation of some snow mass. The snow accumulation process is defined as a material accumulation process during which the mass of snow on a surface increases.",6,True
:has_definition ""A material accumulation process during which ice forms in an environmental material or an existing accumulation of ice increases in mass."" .
